{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center| align = right| direction = vertical| width = 250| header = Known denomination set of Joes| image1 = BR-GUI-A1-Demerary & Essequebo-One Joe (22 Guilders)(1830s).jpg | alt1 = | caption1 = One Joe (22 Guilders) | image2 = BR-GUI-B2-Demerary & Essequebo-Two Joes (22 Guilders each)(1830s).jpg | alt2 = | caption2  = Two Joes (22 Guilders each) | image3 = BR-GUI-B3-Demerary & Essequebo-Three Joes (22 Guilders each)(1830s).jpg | alt3 = | caption3  = Three Joes (22 Guilders each)| image4 = BR-GUI-A4-Demerary & Essequebo-10 Joes (220 Guilders)(1830s).jpg | alt4 = | caption4  = 10 Joes (220 Guilders)| image5 = BR-GUI-A5-Demerary & Essequebo-20 Joes (440 Guilders)(1830s).jpg | alt5 = | caption5  = 20 Joes (440 Guilders) }}

'''Banknotes of Demerary and Essequibo''', issued from 1809{{Sfn|Hazlitt|1896|p=241}} through 1839{{Sfn|Royal Gazette Office|1863|p=9}} were dual-denominated in [[Guilder]]s and ''Joes'', a term used by the British colonists to refer to the Portuguese gold Johannes coin{{Sfn|Halliday|1837|p=192}} and the notes that eventually replaced them.{{Sfn|Dalton|1855|p=291}} Despite roughly 30 years of use, the only ''Joes'' known to exist are unissued remainders from the 1830s.{{Sfn| Cuhaj |2010|p=153}}

==History==

Dating back to at least 1798, the main unit of monetary exchange in the colonies of [[Demerara]] and [[Essequibo (colony)|Essequibo]] was the Portuguese gold Johannes coin{{Sfn|Chalmers|1893|p=94}} which were valued at 22 Dutch guilders.{{Sfn|Royal Gazette Office|1863|p=9}} Exchange rates in the United States in 1797 valued the Portuguese Johannes at $16 (the Spanish [[doubloon]] at $14.93, and the English silver [[Shilling (British coin)|shilling]] at $0.22).{{Sfn|Bates|2015|p=674}} Due to clipping and boring (replaced with brass or copper){{Sfn|Dalton|1855|p=291}} these coins (colloquially referred to as a ''Joe''){{Sfn|Dalton|1855|p=290}} began to lose their intrinsic value. An initial attempt was made to counterstamp or [[chop mark]] valid coins.{{Sfn|Chalmers|1893|p=94}} Eventually (1809) the coins were recalled by the authorities and paper currency, denominated in both Guilders and ''Joes'' were issued.{{Sfn|Royal Gazette Office|1863|p=9}}

==Issuance==

The new paper issue of 1809 introduced 50,000 ''Joes'' equivalent to 1,100,000 guilders.{{Sfn|Dalton|1855|p=291}} This was followed by an additional 25,807 ''Joes'' in 1815–16,{{Sfn|Dalton|1855|p=292}} and 24,193 more in 1824 for a total circulation of just under 100,000 ''Joes''.{{Sfn|Dalton|1855|p=360}} Deemed to be a legal tender,{{Sfn|Dalton|1855|p=291}}{{Sfn|Royal Gazette Office|1863|p=9}} the notes were partially backed by securities in London,{{Sfn|Royal Gazette Office|1863|p=9}} though their ability to be redeemed for gold was questionable.{{Sfn|Chalmers|1893|p=135}}

By 1837, records indicate that 99,989 ''Joes'' had been issued in the following denominations: 1 ''Joe'' (13,258 notes), 2 ''Joes'' (8,189), 3 ''Joes'' (4,201), 5 ''Joes'' (3,150), 10 ''Joes'' (1,700), and 20 ''Joes'' (1,250).{{Sfn| Martin |1839|p=134}} By 1839, there had been reference to a ''half-Joe''.{{Sfn|M’Dermott|1870|p=242}}

==Currently known specimen==

The [[Standard Catalog of World Paper Money]] lists only the unissued remainders of the 1830s. The two issues are distinguished by several design features including an ornate D-E in the upper center (first issue) or a woman with an anchor in the upper left (second issue).{{Sfn| Cuhaj |2010|p=153}}  In addition, the wording of the denomination differs between the series. The first issue lists two denominations: 1 ''Joe'' or 22 Guilders and 10 ''Joes'' or 220 Guilders; the second issue lists four denominations: 1 ''Joe'' of 22 Guilders, 2 ''Joes'' of 22 Guilders each, 3 ''Joes'' of 22 Guilders each, and 10 ''Joes'' of 22 Guilders each.{{Sfn| Cuhaj |2010|p=153}} The illustrated 20 ''Joe'' note is a recent discovery (for the 1830s issue) in the [[National Numismatic Collection]].

