{{double image|right|Flag_of_Germany.svg|150|Flag of East Germany.svg|150|The [[Flag of Germany#Divided Germany|flag of West Germany]]|The [[Flag of Germany#Divided Germany (1949–89)|flag of East Germany]], defaced with a [[National Emblem of the German Democratic Republic|national emblem]]}}
{{double image|right|Flag_of_France.svg|150|Flag_of_Free_France_(1940-1944).svg|150|[[Flag of France]]|Flag of [[Free France]], defaced with a red [[Cross of Lorraine]]}}
{{double image|right|Flag_of_Australia_(converted).svg|150|Australian Border Force Flag.svg|150|The [[flag of Australia]], an already defaced flag|The [[Australian Border Force Flag]], a further defacement}}

'''Defacement''', in [[heraldry]] and [[vexillology]], is the addition of a symbol or [[charge (heraldry)|charge]] to another flag.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://flagspot.net/flags/vxt-dv-d.html#deface |title=Deface |work=Dictionary of Vexillology |publisher=Flags of the World}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nava.org/Flag%20Information/dictionary/index.html#D |title=Deface |work=Illustrated Dictionary of Vexillological Terms |publisher=North American Vexillological Association |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301211311/http://www.nava.org/Flag%20Information/dictionary/index.html |archivedate=2012-03-01 |df= }}</ref> For example, the [[Flag of New Zealand|New Zealand flag]] is the British [[Blue Ensign]] defaced with a [[Crux|Southern Cross]] in the [[Flag terminology#Description of standard flag parts and terms|fly]]. In the context of [[vexillology]], the word "deface" carries no negative connotations, in contrast to general usage. It simply indicates differentiation of the flag from that of another owner by addition of elements. For example, many [[state flag]]s are formed by defacing the national flag with a coat of arms.
==History==
Where countries pass through changes of regime with contrasting ideological orientations (monarchist/republican, fascist/democratic, communist/capitalist, secular/religious etc.)—all of which, despite their differences, claim allegiance to a common national heritage expressed in a venerated national flag—it can happen that a new regime defaces that flag with its own specific emblem while keeping the basic flag design unchanged.{{cn|date=May 2016}} Such changing ideological emblems appeared over time, among others, on the flags of [[Italy]], [[Hungary]], [[Romania]], [[Germany]] (West and East, see illustration) [[Ethiopia]] and [[Iran]]. As a result, during the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956]] and the [[Romanian Revolution of 1989]], insurgents tore out of the national flag the emblem of the regime which they opposed and waved the flag itself with which they identified.  

An already defaced flag can be further defaced. For example, the [[Flag of Australia|Australian flag]] is a defaced [[Blue Ensign]]. The [[Australian Border Force Flag]] is further defaced with the words "Australian border force" in block letters.

In the United States, it is against the [[United States Flag Code|Flag Code]] to deface the [[Flag of the United States|national flag]] with advertising or with any other [[Seal (emblem)| sigil]], image or insignia. Such flags are nevertheless commercially available, depicting the seals of various branches of the [[U.S. military]], [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] related objects such as [[tomahawk (axe)|tomahawk]]s or [[war bonnet]]s, and the like.

It is common for [[association football]] supporters travelling abroad for a match to bring a national flag defaced with the name of their hometown or a similar local identifier.

