'''Foundation deposits''' are the [[Archaeology|archaeological]] remains of the ritual burial of materials under the foundations of buildings.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gerritsen|first=Fokke Albert |title=Local Identities: Landscape and Community|publisher=Amsterdam University Press|year=2003|pages=63–64}}</ref>
<gallery mode=packed style="line-height:130%" widths=165 heights=165 caption="Examples of foundation deposits"> File:Foundation nail IMG 0073-black.jpg|[[Foundation nail]] dedicated by Gudea to Ningirsu. File:Fenestrated axehead-AO 24447-P5280206-gradient.jpg|Fenestrated silver axehead, Middle Bronze Age, found near [[Byblos]] </gallery>
==Ancient Egypt== In the case of [[Ancient Egypt]], foundation deposits took the form of ritual mudbrick lined pits or holes dug at specific points under [[Egyptian temple|temples]] or tombs, which were filled with ceremonial objects, usually amulets, scarabs, food, or ritual miniature tools, and were supposed to prevent the building from falling into ruin.<ref>{{cite book|last=Shaw|first=Ian|title=The Oxford History of Ancient Egypt|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2000|page=103}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebanmappingproject.com/resources/glossary_pop.asp?ID=178|work=Theban Mapping Project|title=Foundation deposit (Glossary entry)|accessdate=2007-06-17}}</ref>
