'''1009'''
* ''September 27.'' The [[Fatimid Caliphate|Fatimid caliph]] [[Al-Hakim bi-Amr Allah|Al-Hakim]] (known as the "Mad Caliph") orders the destruction of the [[Church of the Holy Sepulchre]] in Jerusalem. The subsequent persecution of Christians lasts for more than a decade.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=16}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=11}}
'''1027'''
* The Holy Sepulchre is rebuilt after a Byzantine–Fatimid treaty.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=12}}
'''1055'''
* ''December 18.'' The [[Seljuk Empire|Seljuk ruler]] [[Tughril]] becomes the [[Abbasid Caliphate|Abbasids caliphs]]' protector.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=14}}
'''1063'''
* A Byzantine-Fatimid treaty strengthens the [[List of Byzantine emperors|Byzantine emperors]]' position as the patron of the Christians in the Fatimid Caliphate. The Christian burghers settle in their own fortified quarter in Jerusalem.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=14}}{{sfn|Prawer|1998|p=87}}
'''before 1071'''
* Merchants from [[Amalfi]] establish the Benedictine [[Church of Saint Mary of the Latins|Saint Mary of the Latins Abbey]] in Jerusalem.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=106}}
'''1071'''
* ''August 21.'' [[Battle of Manzikert]]: the Seljuks overcome the Byzantines and invade [[Asia Minor]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=15}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=97}}
* A Seljuk commander, [[Atsiz ibn Uvaq]], captures Jerusalem.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=15}}
'''1074'''
* ''March 1.'' [[Pope Gregory VII]] urges his German and French supporters to assist the Byzantines against the Seljuks.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=16}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=28-29}}
'''1080s'''
* The [[Gregorian Reform|Gregorian]] [[Theology|theologians]], [[Anselm of Lucca]], [[Bonizo of Sutri]] and John of Mantua complete the Roman Catholic ideology of [[Religious war|holy wars]].{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=28-29}}{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=27}}
* A hospital, originally dedicated to [[John the Almsgiver]], is established for male pilgrims in Jerusalem.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=106}}{{sfn|Tyerman|2006|p=253}} 
'''1092'''
* ''November.'' The Seljuk sultan [[Malik-Shah I]] dies and his empire disintegrates into small states.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=19}}{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=42}}
'''1095'''
* ''March.'' The Byzantine Emperor [[Alexios I Komnenos]]'s envoys seek [[Pope Urban II]]'s support for recruiting mercenaries against the Seljuks.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|pp=3-4}}
* ''November 27.'' At the [[Council of Clermont]], Urban II proclaims the [[First Crusade]] for the liberation of the [[Holy Land]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=20}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=37-38}}
* ''December 1.'' [[Raymond IV, Count of Toulouse]] is the first ruler to join the crusade, but the Pope denies to make him its supreme commander.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=20}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=45-46}}
'''1096'''
* ''August 15.'' Godfrey of Bouillon, [[Duke of Lower Lotharingia]], departs for the crusade. His brother, Baldwin of Boulogne, and their kinsman, [[Baldwin II of Jerusalem|Baldwin of Bourcq]], accompany him.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=20}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=37-38}}
'''1097'''
* ''{{circa}} January 20.'' Godfrey swears fealty to Alexios I in Constantinople.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=110-111}}
'''1098'''
* ''March.'' The crusaders offer their assistance to the Fatimids against the Seljuks in return for Jerusalem.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=285}}
* ''July 3.'' After the [[Siege of Antioch|capture of Antioch]], the crusaders delay the military campaign because of the hot summer.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=23}}
* ''August 26.'' [[Al-Afdal Shahanshah|Al-Afdal]], the Fatimid [[vizier]], expels the Seljuks from Jerusalem.{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=42}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=23}}
* ''October 18.'' [[Simeon II of Jerusalem|Simeon II]], the exiled [[Orthodox Patriarch of Jerusalem]], and the papal legate, [[Adhemar of Le Puy]], urge the European warriors to join the crusade in a common letter.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=4}}
'''1099'''
* ''January 13.'' Raymond IV and [[Tancred, Prince of Galilee|Tancred of Hauteville]] depart from the [[Siege of Ma'arra|recently captured Maarrat al-Nu'man]] to continue the crusade.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=276}}
* ''February 14.'' Raymond IV besieges [[Arqa]] because he cannot continue the campaign without other crusader leaders' support.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=282}}
* ''Spring.'' Al-Afdal refutes to make an alliance with the crusaders, but he offers to grant entry into Jerusalem to unarmed pilgrims.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=286}}
* ''{{circa}} April 1.'' The protracted siege of Arqa forces Raymond IV to seek Godfrey's and [[Robert II, Count of Flanders|Robert II of Flanders']] assistance.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=286-287}}
* ''{{circa}} April 10.'' Byzantine envoys inform the crusaders about Alexios I's plan to invade Palestine in late June.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=292-293}}
* ''Early May.'' Ignoring Raymond IV's protests, the crusaders depart for Jerusalem without waiting for the arrival of the Byzantine army.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=294}}
