==First kingdom==

===Establishment===

{{Quote box
|quote=''"''[As] ''the Christian victors came back out of the palace after the very great and cruel slaughter of Saracens, of whom ten thousand fell in that same place, they put to the sword great numbers of gentiles who were running about through the quarters of the city, fleeing in all directions on account of their fear of death: they were piercing through with the sword's point women who had fled into the turreted palaces and dwellings; seizing by the soles of their feet from their mothers' laps or their cradles infants who were still suckling and dashing them against the walls or lintels of the doors and breaking their necks; they were slaughtering some with weapons, or striking them down with stones; they were sparing absolutely no gentile of any age or kind."''
|source = The slaughter of the townspeople in Jerusalem (from [[Albert of Aachen]]'s ''Historia Hierosolymitanae expeditionis'')
|width  = 25%
|align  = right
}}
{{Quote box
|quote=''"''[On] ''the eighth day after the city was captured, they elected Duke Godfrey as prince of the city that he might fight the pagans and guard the Christians. Likewise, on the day of [[Liberation of Saint Peter|Saint Peter in Chains]], they elected as patriarch a most wise and honorable man named Arnulf."''
|source = Godfrey of Bouillon is elected the first crusader ruler of Jerusalem (from the ''[[Gesta Francorum|Gesta Francorum et aliorum Hierosolimitanorum]]'')
|width  = 25%
|align  = right
}}
'''1099'''
* ''May 19.'' The crusaders cross the [[Nahr al-Kalb|Dog River]] into Palestine.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=296}}
* ''June 3.'' The crusaders seize [[Ramla]]. The [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Lydda and Ramla]] is established. The first bishop, [[Robert, Bishop of Lydda and Ramla|Robert]] fixes the tributes payable on his estates to attract Syrian and Frank colonists to settle there. The "custom of Ramla and Lydda" sets the pattern for privileges to colonists. Ramla remains an important center of the production of fresh and dried [[Common fig|figs]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=24}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=297}}{{sfn|Prawer|1998|pp=115, 119-120}}{{sfn|Boas|1999|p=74}}
* ''June 7.'' The crusaders (1,200–1,300 knights and 10,700–10,800 foot-soldiers) reach Jerusalem. The defenders nail crosses on the walls and desecrat them.{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=56}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=298, 309}}
* ''June 17.'' A Genoese fleet captures [[Jaffa]].{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=358}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=304}}
* ''Early July.'' Tancred captures Bethlehem and places his banner over the [[Church of the Nativity]]. The clergymen demand that the Holy Land be transformed into a spiritual realm, protected by secular lords.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=18}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=306}}
* ''July 8.'' A visionary priest, Peter Desiderius, persuades the crusaders to make a penitentiary procession around the walls of Jerusalem.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=308}}{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=68}}
* ''{{circa}} July 15.'' The Saint John Hospital becomes independent of the Saint Mary of the Latins Abbey.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=106}}
* ''July 15.'' The crusaders [[Siege of Jerusalem (1099)|capture Jerusalem]]. They  massacre or enslave almost all local Muslims and Jews.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=316-317}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|pp=50-51}}{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=62}}
* ''July 22.'' Godfrey is elected as the ruler of Jerusalem, but he is not crowned king.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=321}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=19}}
* ''Late July.'' Raymond IV denies to cede the [[Tower of David]] to Godfrey, but his deputy allows Godfrey's soldiers to take possession of it.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=321}}
* ''August 1.'' [[Arnulf of Chocques]] is elected as the first [[Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem]]. He expels the local Christian{{mdash}}[[Armenian Apostolic Church|Armenian]], [[Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria|Copt]], [[Syriac Orthodox Church|Jacobite]], and [[Church of the East|Nestorian]]{{mdash}}clergy from the Holy Sepulchre.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=322}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=21}}
* ''August 12.'' [[Battle of Ascalon]]: the crusaders route Al-Afdal's army.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=21}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=324-325}}
* ''{{circa}} August 30.'' Most crusaders leave the Holy Land for Europe.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=327-330}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=54-55}}
* ''Early September.'' A Pisan fleet arrives at Syria under the command of [[Dagobert of Pisa|Daimbert]], [[Archbishop of Pisa]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=25}}
* ''October 15–December 15.'' Godfrey unsuccessfully [[First Siege of Arsuf|besieges Arsuf]].{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=52}}
* ''December 21.'' Daimbert, [[Bohemond I of Antioch|Bohemond I]] (the first crusader [[prince of Antioch]]), and Godfrey's brother, Baldwin (the first [[count of Edessa]]), come to Jerusalem, accompanied by thousands of pilgrims.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=24}}  
* ''December 25.'' Arnulf abdicates and Daimbert becomes the new Latin patriarch. Godfrey and Bohemond I swear fealty to Daimbert.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=56}}
'''{{circa}} 1100'''
* A man who lives in a house in a town more than a year seizes its possession, according to a decree.{{sfn|Prawer|1998|p=91}}
'''1100'''
* ''February.'' The [[emir]]s (or rulers) of [[Ashkelon|Ascalon]], [[Caesarea]] and [[Acre, Israel|Acre]] pay tribute to Godfrey to prevent him from making plundering raids.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=52}}
* ''February 2.'' Godfrey cedes the fourth of Jaffa to Daimbert.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=57}}
* ''April 1.'' Godfrey promises to cede Jerusalem to Daimbert after the conquest of Ascalon.{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=57-58}}
* ''Early April.'' The Pisan fleet sails for Italy.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=60}}
* ''{{circa}} June 10.'' The [[Doge of Venice]] [[Vitale I Michiel]] arrives at Jaffa at the head of a fleet of 200 ships. His treaty with Godfrey's representatives establishes the Venetians' right to have their own quarter and church in the towns in the Holy Land.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=60}}
* ''July 18.'' Godfrey dies unexpectedly.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=25}}
* ''{{circa}} July 22.'' Godfrey's retainers seize the Tower of David and urge his brother, Baldwin, to claim Jerusalem.{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=50, 61}}{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=66}}
* ''{{circa}} August 1.'' Daimbert asks Bohemond I to prevent Baldwin from coming to Jerusalem.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=61}}
* ''{{circa}} August 15.'' [[Danishmend Gazi]] captures Bohemond I near [[Melitene]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=25}}
* ''August 20.'' Tancred's troops and the Venetians capture [[Haifa]] and massacre the townspeople.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=60}}
* ''October 2.'' Baldwin grants Edessa to Baldwin of Bourcq and departs for Jerusalem.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=62}}
* ''Late October.'' Baldwin's supporters prevent Tancred from seizing Jerusalem and Jaffa. Daimbert takes refugee at a monastery on [[Mount Zion]].{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=63}}
* ''November 9.'' The burghers of Jerusalem ceremoniously receive Baldwin.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=63}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=26}}
* ''November 15–December 21.'' Baldwin makes raids as far as Ascalon and [[Wadi Musa]].{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=63}}
* ''December 25.'' Daimbert crowns Baldwin king in the Church of the Nativity.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=26}}{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=55}}

