===Consolidation===

{{Quote box
|quote=''"''[The keeper of the key of the Tomb of Jesus] ''led me barefoot alone into the holy tomb of the Lord with the lamp which I had brought with me, and told me to place it on the Lord's tomb. And with my own sinful hands I placed it at the place where the most pure feet of Our Lord Jesus Christ lay; at the head stood the lamp of the Greeks and at the breast the lamp of ''[[Mar Saba|[the Greek Orthodox monastery] of Saint Saba]]''... . And then by the grace of God these three lamps were lit, but of the Frankish lamps which had been hung higher up not one was lit. ... In the morning of [[Holy Saturday]] ... all the people gather before the church of the holy Resurrection, a great multitude, both natives of that country and travellers from every land... . ... And the faithful weep torrents of tears ..., for every man then looks into himself and recalls his sins and each says within himself: "Can it be that the holy light will not descend on account of my sins?" ... ''[Baldwin I]'' sent to the hospice of Saint Saba and summoned the abbot and his monks. And the abbot went with his brethren to the tomb of the Lord... . ... ''[Baldwin I]'' commanded the abbot of Saint Sabba to stand above the tomb with his monks... . ... The Latin priests stood on the Great Altar. And ... the orthodox priests and monks ... began to sing [[vespers]], while the Latins ... began mumbling after their own fashion. ... Then suddenly the holy light shone in the holy tomb and a fearful bright flash came from the holy tomb of the Lord. The bishop with four deacons ... took the candle from ''[Baldwin I]'', went into the tomb and lit ''[Baldwin I's]'' candle ... first from the Holy Fire... ."''
|source = Daniel the Traveller's account of the ceremony of the Holy Fire
|width  = 25%
|align  = right
}}
{{Quote box
|quote=''"''[Al-Afdal]'' sent his son, Sharaf al-Ma'ālī, at the head of a large force. They and the Franks met at Yāzūr near Ramla. The Franks suffered a defeat and there was a great slaughter among them. ... When Baldwin saw how serious things were, he feared death or captivity, so threw himself into the grass and hid. Once the Muslims were some distance away, he emerged and went to Ramla. ... ''[Sharaf al-Ma'ālī's]'' followers disagreed about their next objective. Some said, "Let us attack Jerusalem and conquer it." Others said, "Let us attack Jaffa and take it." While they disagreed in this way, a large host of Franks arrived by sea, intending a pilgrimage to Jerusalem. Baldwin directed them to join him on an expedition. They marched to Ascalon, where Sharaf al-Ma'ālī was. He was not strong enough to resist them but God was kind to the Muslims. The Franks from overseas saw how strong Ascalon was and feared a night attack, so they withdrew to Jaffa. ''[Sharaf al-Ma'ālī]'' returned to his father ... ."''
|source = Second Battle of Ramla (from [[Ali ibn al-Athir]]'s Chronicle)
|width  = 25%
|align  = right
}}

'''1100s'''
* The [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] [[Church of Saint Anne, Jerusalem|Church of Saint Anne]] is built in Jerusalem.{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=42}}
'''1101'''
* ''January–February.'' [[Geldemar Carpenel]] accuses Tancred of having unlawfully deprived him of Haifa, but Tancred does not answer the charges.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=65}}
* ''early March.'' After Tancred departures for Antioch to deputize for Bohemond I, Baldwin I distributes his domains between Geldemar Carpenel and [[Hugh of Fauquembergues]]. A papal legate, [[Maurice of Porto]], comes to Jerusalem.{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=65, 73}}
* ''Easter.'' A Genoese fleet arrives at Jaffa.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=67}} The Greek Orthodox monks are allowed to return to the Holy Sepulchre to secure the celebration of the Holy Fire.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=26}} 
* ''May.'' Baldwin I and the Genoese capture Arsuf and Caesarea.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=67}}
* ''August–September.'' The [[Sultanate of Rum|Seljuk Sultan of Rum]] [[Kilij Arslan I]] and his allies massacre most crusaders of the [[Crusade of 1101]] in Asia Minor.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|pp=65-66}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=22}}
* ''September 7.'' [[Battle of Ramla (1101)|First Battle of Ramla]]: Baldwin I routes a Fatimid army, but one-third of his troops perishes in the battlefield.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=70}}
* ''Winter.'' Daimbert is deposed at a church council in the papal legate's presence.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=55}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=27}}
'''1102'''
* ''Easter.'' [[Stephen, Count of Blois]], [[Stephen I, Count of Burgundy]] and other survivors of the Crusade of 1101 stay in Jerusalem.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=70}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=27}}
* ''May 17.'' [[Battle of Ramla (1102)|Second Battle of Ramla]]: Al-Afdal's son, Sharaf al-Ma'ali, almost annihilates the Frank army. Baldwin I appeals for help to Tancred.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=70}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=67}}
* ''May 28.'' After gathering new troops, Baldwin I forces Sharaf al-Ma'ali to return to Egypt.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=70}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=27}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=67}}
* ''late May.'' Tancred tries to achieve Daimbert's restoration, but the new papal legate, [[Robert of Paris|Robert of St Eusebio]], confirms Daimbert's deposition. A pious cleric, [[Evremar]], is appointed as the Latin patriarch.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=74}}{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=56}}
'''1103'''
* ''April.'' Baldwin I besieges Acre, but cannot capture it.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=68}}
* ''July.'' Baldwin I is seriously wounded in a skirmish near Caesarea.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=117}}
'''1103–1106'''
* Baldwin I forces his Armenian wife (now known as [[Arda of Armenia|Arda]]) into a monastery. She moves to Constantinople.{{sfn|Phillips|2010|pp=50-51}}{{sfn|Hodgson|2007|pp=141-142}}
'''{{circa}} 1104'''
* The Jacobite metropolitan of Jerusalem Ignatius II persuades Baldwin I to restore the estates of his see to him.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=194}}
'''1104'''
* ''May 26.'' Baldwin I captures Acre with the assistance of Genoese and Pisan fleets. The fields around the town are turned over to [[sugarcane]] growning and [[Sugar refinery|sugar refineries]] are established after the Italian merchants starts to deliver sugar to Europe.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=68}}{{sfn|Boas|1999|p=79}}
* ''Autumn.'' Daimbert sails for Italy to achieve his restoration in Rome.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=56}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=28}}
'''1105'''
* ''February 28.'' Raymond IV dies and his cousin, [[William II Jordan|William Jordan]] continues the [[siege of Tripoli]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=28}}
* ''August 27.'' [[Battle of Ramla (1105)|Third Battle of Ramla]]: Baldwin I defeats the united Fatimid and Seljuk armies.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=71}} 
'''{{circa}} 1107'''
* Baldwin I starts to grant "[[money fief]]s"{{mdash}}a share of royal revenues{{mdash}}to his knights.{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|pp=68-69}}
'''1106–1108'''
* [[Daniel the Traveller]], an abbot from [[Kievan Rus']], makes a pilgrimage in the Holy Land. He visits Orthodox monasteries, many of which have been ruined.{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=154}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=107}}
'''1107'''
* [[Pope Paschal II]] reinstates Daimbert as patriarch.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=56}}
* ''June 16.'' Daimbert dies in [[Messina]].{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=56}} 
'''1108'''
* The new papal legate, Archbishop [[Ghibbelin of Arles]], deposes Evremar at a church council. Ghibbelin is elected as the Latin patriarch.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=57}}
'''1109'''
* ''March.'' Raymond IV's son, [[Bertrand, Count of Toulouse|Bertrand]], lays claim to Raymond IV's inheritance against William Jordan. William Jordan makes an alliance with Tancred and Bertrand swears fealty to Baldwin I.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=28}} 
* ''April.'' Baldwin I summons Tancred and Tancred's opponents, Bertrand, Baldwin II of Edessa and [[Joscelin I, Count of Edessa|Joscelin of Courtenay]] to a general assembly at the crusaders' camp at [[Tripoli, Lebanon|Tripoli]] in the name of the "whole church of Jerusalem". The assembly confirms Bertrand's claim to Tripoli and Baldwin I grants [[Principality of Galilee|Galilee]] to Tancred.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=30}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=91-92}}
* ''July 12.'' The crusaders capture and sack Tripoli. Baldwin I grants a safe-conducts to the burghers, but he cannot prevent the Genoese from killing many of them.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=80}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=92}}
'''1110'''
* ''May 12.'' Baldwin I and a Genoese fleet capture [[Beirut]]. The crusaders massacre the townspeople.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=80}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=31}}
* ''early summer.'' Baldwin I and Bertrand make a joint military campaign against [[Mawdud]], the atabeg of Mosul, to protect Edessa.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=80}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=31}}
* ''December 4.'' Baldwin I, [[Sigurd I of Norway]] and a Venetian fleet [[Siege of Sidon|capture Sidon]]. The Muslim burghers remain in the town.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=31}}{{sfn|Prawer|1998|pp=85-86}} 
'''1111'''
* ''February 17 and 24.'' A [[qadi]] from Aleppo, [[Ibn al-Khashshab (died 1125)|Ibn al-Khashshab]], a Hashemite [[sharif]], and many Muslim commoners urge the Seljuk Sultan [[Muhammad I Tapar]] in the principal mosques in Bagdad to start a holy war against the crusaders.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|pp=81-82}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=100}}
* The Pope confirms the jurisdiction of the Latin Patriarchs of Jerusalem over the newly established [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Sidon|Roman Catholic bishoprics of Sidon]] and [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Beirut|Beirut]], ignoring the traditional boundary between the patriarchal sees of [[Patriarch of Antioch|Antioch]] and Jerusalem.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=27}}
'''1112'''
* ''Lent.'' Patriarch Ghibbelin dies.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=61}}
* ''December.'' Arnoulf of Chocques elected as the Latin patriarch.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=112}} 
'''1113'''
* ''May–June.'' Mawdud and [[Toghtekin]], the atabeg of Damascus, invade Galilee.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|pp=81-82}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=100}}
* ''June 28.'' [[Battle of Al-Sannabra]]: Mawdud and Toghtekin defeat Baldwin I.{{sfn|Hillenbrand|1999|p=305}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=32}}
* ''July–August.'' Mawdud makes raids as far as Ascalon.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=32}}
* ''August.'' Baldwin I marries the wealthy [[Adelaide del Vasto]] after promising to name her son, [[Roger II of Sicily]], as his heir.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=114}}{{sfn|Phillips|2010|p=51}}
* ''Late.'' Pope Paschal II [[Pie postulatio voluntatis|confirms the autonomy of the monks of the Saint John Hospital]] (or Hospitallers).{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=32}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=107}}
'''1114'''
* The [[Canon (priest)|canons]] of the Holy Sepulchre adopt the [[Rule of St. Augustine]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=32}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=359}}
'''1115'''
* The papal legate, Berengar, [[Bishop of Orange]], deposes Patriarch Arnulf primarily for Baldwin I's bigamious marriage.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=359}}
* [[Pagan (chancellor)|Pagan]] is the first [[chancellor of Jerusalem]].{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=105}}
* The construction of [[Montreal (Crusader castle)|Montreal Castle]] in [[Oultrejordain]] begins. Baldwin I grants estates to the knights and commoners who settle near the castle. The region develops into an important center of [[sugarcane]] growning.{{sfn|Boas|1999|p=79}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=33}}{{sfn|Prawer|1998|pp=109-110}}
'''{{circa}} 1116'''
* Castles are built near [[Petra]] and [[Aqaba]] to control the caravan routes between Egypt and Syria.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=105}}
* Baldwin I grants liberties to local Christians who move from Oultrejourdain to Jerusalem.{{sfn|Prawer|1998|p=93}}
'''1117'''
* ''April 25.'' Adelaide departs for Sicily after her marriage to Baldwin I was annulled at a church council convoked by Arnoulf of Chocques.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=115}}
* ''July 19.'' The Pope appoints Arnoulf of Chocques as the Latin patriarch.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=115}}
'''1118'''
* ''March.'' Baldwin I invades Egypt. He falls seriously ill in [[Pelusium]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=33}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=94}}
* ''April 2.'' Baldwin I dies at [[Arish]]. Envoys are sent to his brother, [[Eustace III, Count of Boulogne]], offering him the throne.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=33}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=94}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=119}}
* ''April 14.'' Baldwin II of Edessa comes to Jerusalem. Patriarch Arnulf and Joscelin of Courtenay achieve his election as Baldwin I's successor.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=33}}{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=411}}
* ''Late April.'' Patriarch Arnulf dies. Baldwin II secures the direct royal control of the most important towns and the noblemen swear fealty to him at a general assembly.{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=118, 120}}
* ''May.'' Toghtekin invades Galilee. Al-Afdal gathers his troops at Ascalon and Toghtekin joins him.{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=411}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=34}}
* ''May–July.'' Baldwin II and troops from Antioch and Tripoli prevent Al-Afdal and Toghtekin from launching a joint campaign against the kingdom.{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=412}}
* ''Late summer.'' Baldwin II invades Damascene territory and routes Toghtekin's son, [[Taj al-Muluk Buri]].{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=412}}
* ''August–September.'' [[Patriarch Warmund of Jerusalem|Warmund of Picquigny]] is elected as the Latin patriarch.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=120}}
'''1119'''
* Patriarch Warmund confirms the religious community established by [[Hugues de Payens]] and other knights to protect the pilgrims. Baldwin II cedes a part of the [[Al-Aqsa Mosque|royal palace]], identified as [[Solomon's Temple]], to them (hence they are known as [[Knights Templar|Templars]]).{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=34}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=134}}{{sfn|Phillips|2010|p=277}}
* ''June 28.'' [[Battle of Ager Sanguinis|Battle of the "Field of Blood"]]: the [[Artuqids|Artuqid]] ruler of [[Mardin]] [[Ilghazi]] almost annihilates the Antiochene army.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=34}}{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=413}}
* ''Late July.'' Baldwin II is acknowledged as regent for the absent minor prince of Antioch, [[Bohemond II of Antioch|Bohemond II]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=34}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=124-125}}
* ''August 14.'' [[Battle of Hab]]: Baldwin II forces Ilghazi and Toghtekin to withdraw from Antiochene territory.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=125}}{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|pp=413-414}}
* ''August–September.'' Baldwin II grants the County of Edessa to Joscelin.{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=414}}
* ''December 25.'' Baldwin II is crowned king in Bethlehem.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=119}}
'''1120'''
* ''January 16.'' [[Council of Nablus]]: the Jerusalemite prelates and barons adopt laws against sexual misconduct and confirm the right of the Church to collect the [[tithe]]. Baldwin II abolishes customs on food delivered to Jerusalem.{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=129-131}}{{sfn|Prawer|1998|p=94}}
* ''January 23.'' Baldwin II appeals to [[Pope Calixtus II]] and to Venice for assistance against the Muslim powers.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=35}}
* ''May.'' [[Fulk, King of Jerusalem|Fulk V, Count of Anjou]] comes to the Holy Land.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=146}}
* ''June.'' Ilghazi invades Antiochene territories. Baldwin II returns to Syria, ignoring his Jerusalemite vassals' opposition to the campaign.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=137}}
'''1120s'''
* The canons of the Holy Sepulchre open a school.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=160}}
'''1121'''
* ''April–June.'' Baldwin II conducts a series of military expeditions in Syria.{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=416}}
* ''June.'' Toghtekin invades Galilee, forcing Baldwin II to return from Syria.{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|pp=416-417}}
* ''July.'' Baldwin II captures and destroys the fortress built by Toghtekin at [[Jerash]] in the previous year.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=35}}
* ''August–October.'' Baldwin II conducts new campaigns in Syria.{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=416}}
'''1122'''
* ''January.'' Fulk V hires 100 knights for the defence of the Holy Land before his departure for Europe.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=146}}
* ''Early.'' Baldwin II forces [[Pons, Count of Tripoli]] into obedience.{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=417}}
* ''September 13.'' Joscelin I is captured by [[Nur al-Daulak Balak]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=36}}
* ''Autumn.'' Baldwin II appoints [[Geoffrey the Monk|Geoffrey of Marash]] to administer the County of Edessa.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=36}}
'''1123'''
* ''April 18.'' Balak captures Baldwin II in Syria.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=36}}
* ''Late April.'' Patriarch Warmund convokes a general assembly which elects [[Eustace Grenier]] as [[Bailiff of Jerusalem|baillif]] (or regent) for the captive Baldwin II.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=140}}{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=421}}
* ''May.'' The Doge of Venice [[Domenico Michiel]] arrives at Jaffa and the Venetians defeat a Fatimid fleet.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=140}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=37}}
* ''May 29.'' Fatimid troops invade the kingdom, but the Jerusalemite army defeats them near [[Yibna|Ibelin]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=37}}
* ''June 15.'' Eustace Grenier dies. [[William I of Bures]] is elected as baillif.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=140}}
* ''December.'' ''[[Pactum Warmundi]]:'' Patriarch Warmund, William I of Bures and the chancellor, Pagan, grant privileges to the Venetians.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=140}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=37}}
'''1123 or 1124'''
* A group of barons offers the throne to [[Charles I, Count of Flanders]], but he does not accept the offer.{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=143-144}}{{sfn|Hodgson|2007|p=76}}
'''1124'''
* ''February 16.'' The Venetians and the Franks lay [[Siege of Tyre (1124)|siege to Tyre]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=37}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=141}}
* ''July 7 or 8.'' The fall of Tyre to the Franks. The Muslim burghers remain in the town. The Venetians receive more than 15 nearby villages, and they grant most of them to Venetian noble families. The region becomes the most important center of [[sugarcane]] growning in the kingdom.{{sfn|Boas|1999|p=79}}{{sfn|Prawer|1998|pp=85-86, 147-148}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=37}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=141}}
* ''August 29.'' Ilghazi son's, Timurtash, releases Baldwin II for ransom.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=138}}

