===Heyday===
{{Quote box
|quote=''"''For nine years after their founding, the'' [Knights Templar] ''wore secular clothing. They used such garments as the people, for their soul's salvation, gave them. In'' [1129] ''there was held in France, at Troyes, a council at which the Lord Archbishops of Reims and Sens and their suffragans were present, as well as ... the legate of the apostolic see, and the Abbots of Citeaux, Clairvaux, Pontigny, with many others. This council, by command of the Lord Pope Honorius and the Lord Stephen, Patriarch of Jerusalem, established a rule for the knights and assigned them a white habit. ... From this time onward'' [the Knights'] ''numbers began to grow and their possessions began to multiply. Later, in Pope Eugene's time, it is said that both the knights and their humbler servants, called sergeants, began to affix crosses made of red cloth to their mantles, so as to distinguish themselves from others. ... They are said to have immense possessions..., so that there is now not a province in the Christian world which has not bestowed upon the aforesaid brothers a portion of its goods. It is said today that their wealth is equal to the treasures of kings. ... Although they maintained their establishment honorably for a long time and fulfilled their vocation with sufficient prudence, later, because of the neglect of humility..., they withdrew from the Patriarch of Jerusalem, by whom their Order was founded ... and to whom they denied the obedience which their predecessors rendered. They have also taken away tithes and first fruits from God's churches, have disturbed their possessions, and have made themselves exceedingly troublesome. "''
|source = William of Tyre about the Knights Templar
|width  = 25%
|align  = right
}}
'''1124'''
* ''October 6.'' Baldwin II lays siege to Aleppo.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=37}}
* ''Late.'' Timurtash refuses to assist the burghers of Aleppo. Ibn al-Khashshab turns to the atabeg of Mosul [[Aqsunqur al-Bursuqi]] for assistance.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=37}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|pp=97-98}}
'''1125'''
* ''January 25.'' Al-Bursuqi forces Baldwin II to lift the siege of Aleppo and units Aleppo with Mosul.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=38}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=98}}
* ''April 3.'' Baldwin II returns to Jerusalem for the first time since 1121.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=38}}
* ''May 2.'' ''Privilegium Balduini:'' Baldwin II modifies the terms of the ''Pactum Warmundi'' to strengthen royal authority.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=38}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=142}}
* ''June 11.'' Baldwin II, Pons and Joscelin I defeat the united forces of Al-Bursuqi and Toghtekin near Azaz.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=143}}
'''1126'''
* ''Late January.'' Baldwin II defeats Toghtekin on the plain of [[Marj al-Saffar]].{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=144}}{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=426}}
* ''March–July.'' Baldwin II and Pons conduct joint campaigns in Syria.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=38}}
* ''October.'' Bohemond II comes to Antioch and marries Baldwin II's daughter, [[Alice of Antioch|Alice]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=39}}
'''1127'''
* ''April.'' The Seljuk Sultan [[Mahmud II of Great Seljuq|Mahmud II]] appoints [[Imad ad-Din Zengi]] to administer Mosul and Aleppo.{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=429}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=113}}
* ''October.'' William I of Bures is sent to France to offer the hand of Baldwin II's eldest daughter, [[Melisende, Queen of Jerusalem|Melisende]], to Fulk V of Anjou.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=39}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=145}}
'''1127'''
* ''Summer.'' Baldwin II mediates a reconciliation between Bohemond II and Joscelin I in Syria.{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=428}}
'''1128'''
* ''January.'' Zengi's troops capture Aleppo.{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=429}}
* ''July 27.'' Patriarch Warmund dies.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=151}}{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=67}}
* ''Summer or Autumn.'' Baldwin II's relative, [[Stephen of La Ferté]], is made the Latin patriarch.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=151}}{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=67}}
'''1129'''
* ''January.'' The Templars' ''[[Latin Rule]]'' is confirmed at the [[Council of Troyes]].{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=146-147}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=40}}
* ''May.'' Fulk V comes to Jerusalem and marries Melisende after Baldwin II promises to appoint him as his sole heir.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=40}}
* ''September 4.'' Toghtekin's son and successor, [[Taj al-Muluk Buri]], orders a purge against the Assassins in Damascus. Their leader  Ismail al-Ajami offers to cede [[Banias]] to Baldwin II.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=40}}{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=430}}
* ''November.'' The Franks seize Banias and invade Damascene territory, but Buri routes them on Marj al-Saffar.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=40}}{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|pp=430-431}}
'''{{circa}} 1130'''
* Patriarch Stephen demands Jaffa from Baldwin II.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=151}}{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=68}}
* Leprous knights establish the [[Order of Saint Lazarus]].{{sfn|Tyerman|2006|pp=256-257}}
'''1130'''
* ''February.'' Bohemond II is killed during a raid and the Antiochene lords offer the regency for his daughter by Alice, [[Constance of Antioch|Constance]], to Baldwin II. Alice seeks Zengi's assistance against Baldwin II, but he seizes Antioch and appoints Joscelin I to administer it.{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=431}}
* ''June.'' Patriarch Stephen dies. His successor, [[William of Malines]], abandons Stephen's claims to Jaffa.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=151}}{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|pp=68-69}}
'''1131'''
* ''August.'' The dying Baldwin II names Fulk, Melisende and their son, Baldwin as his co-heirs.{{sfn|Philips|2010|pp=52-53}}{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=432}}
* ''August 21.'' Baldwin II dies in Jerusalem.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=40}}
* ''September 14.'' Fulk and Melisende are crowned in the Holy Sepulchre. Fulk starts replacing his late father-in-law's officials with his own supporters.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=41}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=149}}{{sfn|Philips|2010|p=68}}
'''{{circa}} 1132–{{circa}} 1135'''
* Fulk's sister, [[Ermengarde of Anjou (d. 1146)|Ermengarde]], makes a pilgrimage in the Holy Land.{{sfn|Hodgson|2007|p=41}} 
'''1132'''
* ''Summer.'' Alice and Pons conclude an alliace against Fulk, but Fulk prevents her from assuming the regency in Antioch and defeats Pons near [[Chastel Rouge]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=41}}{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=433}}
* ''December 21.'' Buri's son and successor, [[Shams-ul-Mulk Isma'il]], captures Banias.{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=433}}
'''1133'''
* ''Spring.'' Fulk and Pons defeat Turkmen raiders. Fulk overcomes Zengi's general, Sawar, near [[Qinnasrin]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=41}}
* Patriarch Stephen begins the construction of [[Chastel Hernaut]] to protect the pilgrims on the road between Jaffa and Jerusalem.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=41}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=162}}
'''1134'''
* ''Late.'' [[Walter I Grenier]] accuses his stepfather, [[Hugh II of Jaffa]], of plotting against Fulk. Hugh rose up and seeks the Fatimids' assistance. Patriarch William mediates a reconciliation and Hugh leaves for Italy.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=42}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=154}}
* Fulk orders the construction of a castle at [[Bethgibelin]] near Ascalon.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=162}}
'''{{circa}} 1135'''
* Fulk commissiones a [[Melisende Psalter|splendid psalter]] for Melisende.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=160}}
'''1135'''
* ''August.'' Fulk allows Alice to return to Antioch.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=42}}
'''1136'''
* ''April.'' Fulk's candidate, [[Raymond of Poitiers]], marries Constance in Antioch.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=42}}
* Fulk gives Bethgibelin to the Hospitallers. The grant shows the militarization of the order.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=162}}
'''1137'''
* ''July 11.'' [[Battle of Ba'rin]]: Zengi defeats Fulk and [[Raymond II, Count of Tripoli]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=42}}{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=438}}
* ''September.'' The [[Byzantine Emperor]] [[John II Komnenos]] besieges Antioch. Fulk authorizes Raymond to swear fealty to the Emperor.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=42}}{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=439}}
'''1138'''
* ''February 5.'' Melisende establishes the Saint Lazarus Abbey at Bethany and appoints her sister, [[Ioveta of Bethany|Yvetta]], as its first abbess.{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=157-158, 361}}
* ''July.'' The [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Tyre|archbishop of Tyre]] [[Patriarch Fulk of Jerusalem|Fulcher of Angoulême]] cannot persuade [[Pope Innocent II]] to restore the authority of Tyre over bishoprics in the County of Tripoli and the Principality of Antioch. In retaliation for Fulcher's independent action, Patriarch William takes direct control of the see of Tyre and its suffragans.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|pp=70-71}}
'''1139'''
* Pope Innocent II orders Patriarch William to restore the see of Tyre to Archbishop Fulcher.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=71}}
* ''Summer.'' Fulk and his son-in-law, [[Thierry, Count of Flanders]], capture a cave fortress at [[Ajloun]].{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=163}}
* ''December.'' The commander of the Damascene army, [[Mu'in ad-Din Unur]], makes an alliance with Fulk and offers Banias to him.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=44}}{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=442}}
'''1140'''
* ''May.'' Zengi besieges Damascus, but the gathering of Jerusalemite troops near Tiberias forces him to lift the siege.{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|pp=442-443}}
* ''June 12.'' Jerusalemite and Damascene troops capture Banias.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=44}}{{sfn|Nicholson|1969|p=443}}
'''1141'''
* The papal legate, Bishop [[Alberic of Ostia]], consecrates the [[Dome of the Rock]], transforming it into a church.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=177}}
'''1142'''
* Castle Blanchegarde is built near Ascalon and [[Al-Karak|Kerak]] is erected in Oultrejourdain. Frank colonists settle near Kerak which develops into an important center of rural industries. Before long, a large communal oven is built in Kerak.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=162}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=45}}{{sfn|Prawer|1998|p=111}}{{sfn|Boas|1999|p=75}}
* ''December 25.'' Patriarch William crowns and [[Anointing|anoints]] Fulk and Melisende's son, Baldwin III, in the Holy Sepulchre. Melisende is crowned for the second time together with her son.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=45}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=174}}
'''1143'''
* ''November 10.'' Fulk dies after a riding accident.{{sfn|Philips|2010|p=72}}
* Melisende appoints her cousin, [[Manasses of Hierges]], as [[constable of Jerusalem|constable]].{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=176}}
'''1144'''
* ''Spring.'' Baldwin III crushes a riot in Wadi Musa.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=46}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=180}}
* ''December 24.'' Zengi [[Siege of Edessa|captures Edessa]] before the relieving army sent by Melisende reaches the town.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=46}}

