===Towards Muslim unity===

{{See also|Crusader invasions of Egypt|Quantum praedecessores}}

'''1145'''
* ''September 25.'' Patriarch William dies.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=72}}
* ''November.'' Envoys are sent from the crusader states to European rulers seeking their assistance for the recovery of Edessa.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=46}}
* ''December 1.'' [[Pope Eugenius III]] urges King [[Louis VII of France]] to launch a [[Second Crusade|new crusade]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=46}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=184-185}}
'''1146'''
* ''January 25.'' Fulcher of Angoulême is elected as the Latin patriarch.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=72}}
* ''September 14.'' A eunuch slave murders Zengi. Zengi's younger son, [[Nur ad-Din (died 1174)|Nur ad-Din]], seizes Aleppo.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|pp=138, 145}}{{sfn|Hillenbrand|1999|p=116}}
'''1146–1153'''
* Frank colonists receive houses, arable lands, vineyards and a share in the olive groves in the royal domain near Casal Imbert. They are to give two-thirds of the olives and one-third of the crops to the king. The king held a monopoly over the bakery and the communal bath.{{sfn|Boas|1999|p=61}}{{sfn|Prawer|1998|pp=141-142}} 
'''1147'''
* ''Spring.'' Baldwin III makes a raid against the fertile Hauran region near Damascus.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=183}}
* ''May–June.'' Nur ad-Din forces Baldwin III to withdraw from Damascene territory.{{sfn|Lock|2006|pp=47-48}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=184}}
'''1148'''
* Melisende donates a village to the Jacobite metropolitanate of Jerusalem.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=178}}
* ''March 19.'' Louis VII and the French crusaders reach Antioch.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=49}}
* ''{{circa}} April 15.'' [[Conrad III of Germany]] and the German crusaders land at Acre.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=49}}
* ''June 24.'' [[Council of Acre]]: Louis VII, Conrad III, Melisende, Baldwin III and other crusader leaders decide to conquer Damascus.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=49}}{{sfn|Philips|2010|p=96}}
* ''July 23–27.'' The crusaders besiege Damascus, but troops coming from the Muslim countries force them to lift the siege.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=178}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=49}}
* ''September 8.'' Conrad III and his army leave the Holy Land.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=49}}
'''1149'''
* First reference to a Court of Burgesses in Jerusalem. Headed by the local viscounts, the Courts of Burgesses judge the Frank commoners in about 40 towns.{{sfn|Prawer|1998|pp=263-264}}
* ''May.'' Louis VII and the French crusaders depart for France.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=50}}
* ''June 29.'' [[Battle of Inab]]: Nur ad-Din's general, [[Shirkuh]], defeats and kills Raymond of Poitiers.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=150}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=194}}
* ''July 15.'' Patriarch Fulcher consecrates the Romanesque basilica of the Holy Sepulchre.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=74}}
* ''August.'' Baldwin III leads a relief army to Antioch.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=194}}
'''before 1150'''
* Special courts of justice are set up to hear cases relating to fugitive serfs.{{sfn|Prawer|1998|p=204}}
'''1150'''
* ''May.'' Baldwin III grants the newly built castle of [[Gaza City|Gaza]] to the Templars.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=51}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=200-201}}
* ''May 4.'' Turkoman raiders capture Joscelin II.{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=533}}
* ''May–June.'' Melisende's supporters does not join Baldwin III's military campaign to Syria. Baldwin III permits Joscelin II's wife, Beatrice, to sale the remnants of the County of Edessa to the Byzantines.{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=195-195}}{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=534}}
'''1150s'''
* Baldwin III orders the collection of all coins and the issue of new ones to secure the royal control of coinage.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=218}} 
* Baldwin, Viscount of Nablus, brings Muslim and Frank colonists to his estates.{{sfn|Prawer|1998|p=110}}
* The Hospitallers settle colonists both from Palestinian towns and from France, Northern Italy and Catalonia in their estates at [[Bayt Jibrin]].{{sfn|Prawer|1998|pp=120-121}}
'''1151'''
* Melisende makes her younger son, Amalric, the count of Jaffa.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=52}}
* ''Spring.'' Nur ad-Din besieges Damascus, but Baldwin III's invasion of the Hauran forces him to abandon the siege.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=51}}
* ''July.'' A Fatimid fleet makes a raid along the coast.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=51}}
* ''Late.'' Assassins murder Raymond II. The Tripolitan lords swear allegiance to the minor [[Raymond III of Tripoli]] and his mother, [[Hodierna of Jerusalem]], at Baldwin III's presence.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=51}}{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=536}}
'''1152'''
* ''April.'' Baldwin III demands the division of the kingdom from his mother. He appoints [[Humphrey II of Toron]] as constable and captures Manasses of Hierges' [[Mirabel (castle)|castle at Mirabel]]. He forces Melisende to abdicate and deprives Amalric of Jaffa.{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=196-197}}
'''1153'''
* ''January 25.'' The crusaders lay [[Siege of Ascalon|siege to Ascalon]].{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=201}}
* ''Spring.'' Baldwin III gives consents to the marriage of Constance of Antioch and [[Raynald of Châtillon]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=52}}{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=540}}
* ''August 23.'' The Franks capture Ascalon, thus completing the conquest of the Western coast of the [[Mediterranean Sea]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=53}}{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=538}}
'''1154'''
* Baldwin III restores Jaffa to Amalric and also grants Ascalon to him.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=197, 404}}
* A royal confirmation of previous grants shows that non-Frank peasants (known as ''rustici'' or ''villani'') are regularly donated to the Hospitallers.{{sfn|Prawer|1998|pp=206-207}} 
* ''April 25.'' Nur ad-Din captures Damascus, uniting the Muslim lands in Syria.{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=538}}
'''{{circa}} 1155'''
* About 500 French, Catalan, Italian and Frank peasants live in a village, known as Magna Mahumeria, on the estates of the canons of the Holy Sepulchre near [[Al-Bireh]]. This typical planned village of the age developed around a fortified manor house and consisted of small and narrow{{mdash}}{{convert|4|x|10|m|abbr=on}}{{mdash}}houses with wide [[rubble]] and [[ashlar]] walls. The villagers collect water on the roofs to feed cisterns through pipes and channels. Documents refer to smiths, carpenters, builders, gardeners and shoemakers living in the village.{{sfn|Prawer|1998|pp=126-127}}{{sfn|Boas|1999|pp=63-65}}
'''1155'''
* ''June.'' Nur ad-Din and Baldwin III conclude a one-year truce.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=53}}{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=539}}
* ''October–November.'' Patriarch Fulcher and most of his suffragans accuse the Hospitallers of abusing their privileges, but [[Pope Hadrian IV]] does not condemn the knights.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=74}}
'''1156'''
* ''June.'' The truce is renewed for a year after Nur ad-Din promises a tribute to Baldwin III.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=53}}{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=539}}
'''1157'''
* ''May–June.'' Nur ad-Din besieges Banias, but Baldwin III relieves the fortress.{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=539}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=210-211}}
* ''July.'' Nur ad-Din again besieges Banias, but the united armies of Baldwin III, Raymond III and Raynald force him to withdraw his troops.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=54}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=211}}
* ''September.'' [[Thierry, Count of Flanders]] and Flemish crusaders land at Beirut.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=211}}
* ''November.'' The united crusader forces capture [[Shaizar]]. Baldwin III grants it to Thierry, but after a debate between Thierry and Raynald about its status, the crusaders abandon it.{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=211-212}}
* ''November 20.'' Patriarch Fulcher dies.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=75}}
* ''Late.'' Baldwin III's half-sister, [[Sibylla of Anjou|Sibylla]], and aunt, Yvetta, achieve the election of a French cleric, [[Patriarch Amalric of Jerusalem|Amalric of Nesle]], as the Latin patriarch. The archbishop of Caesarea and the bishop of Bethlehem appeal to the Holy See against his election.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=76}}
'''1158'''
* ''February.'' The united crusader forces capture [[Harem, Syria|Haram]].{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=542}}
* ''Spring.'' Baldwin III and Thierry make a raid against Damascene territory.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=54}}{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=542}}
* ''May.'' Nur ad-Din besieges the castle of Habis Jaldak near Tiberias.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=54}}{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=542}}
* ''July 15.'' Baldwin III and Thierry relieve Habis Jaldak.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=54}}{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=542}} 
* ''September.'' Baldwin III marries a niece of the Byzantine Emperor [[Manuel I Komnenos]], [[Theodora Komnene, Queen of Jerusalem|Theodora]].{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=212}}
* ''Late.'' Pope Hadrian IV confirms Amalric of Nesle's election as patriarch.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=76}}
'''1159'''
* ''Spring.'' After lengthy negotiations, Manuel I and Baldwin III conclude an alliance against Nur ad-Din near Antioch.{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|pp=543-545}}
* ''April 12.'' Baldwin III and Raynald ceremoniusly receive Manuel I in Antioch.{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=544}}   
* ''May.'' After Nur ad-Din releases his Christian prisoners and offers an alliance  against th Seljuks of Rum, Manuel I leaves Syria for Constantinople.{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=545}}
* Baldwin III persuades the prelates and barons to remain neutral in the conflict between [[Pope Alexander III]] and [[Antipope|his rival]], [[Antipope Victor IV (1159–1164)|Victor IV]] at their general assembly in [[Nazareth]]. Later the prelates acknowledge Alexander III as the lawful pope.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=76}}
'''1160'''
* ''November.'' After Nur ad-Din's soldiers capture Raynald, Baldwin III appoints the [[Latin patriarch of Antioch]], [[Aimery of Limoges]] to administer Antioch.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=55}}{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=546}}
'''1161'''
* ''September 11.'' Melisende dies.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=55}}
'''1163'''
* ''February 10.'' Baldwin III dies childless in Beirut.{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=547}}
* ''{{circa}} February 15.'' The prelates and barons elect Baldwin III's brother, Amalric, as king only after Amalric's marriage to [[Agnes of Courtenay]] is [[Declaration of nullity|annulled]]. Amalric achieves the confirmation of their children's legitimacy.{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=549}}
* ''February 18.'' Amalric is crowned king.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=56}}
* ''September.'' Amalric besieges [[Bilbeis]] in Egypt. The Egyptians cut the dikes, forcing him to return to Jerusalem.{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=550}}
'''{{circa}} 1164'''
* Amalric's ''[[Assise sur la ligece]]'' obliges the vassals of his own vassals to swear fealty to him.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=236}} 
'''1164'''
* ''Early.'' Amalric urges Louis VII to send reinforcements to the Holy Land.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=56}}
* ''April.'' Nur ad-Din sends Shirkuh to Egypt to restore the former Fatimid ''vizier'', [[Shawar]].{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=550}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=162}}{{sfn|Hillenbrand|1999|p=117}}
* ''May.'' Shawar denies to pay a tribute to Nur ad-Din. After Shirkuh captures Bilbeis, Shawar seeks Amalric's assistance.{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=550}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|pp=162-163}}
* ''August–October.'' Amalric besieges Bilbeis.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=57}}
* ''August 10.'' [[Battle of Harim]]: Nur ad-Din routes the united armies of [[Bohemond III of Antioch]], Raymond III, [[Thoros II, Prince of Armenia|Thoros II of Armenian Cilicia]], and [[Constantine Kalamanos]], the Byzantine governor of [[Cibyrrhaeot Theme|Cilicia]].{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=240}}
* ''September.'' Nur ad-Din captures Banias.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=57}}
* ''October.'' Amalric and Shirkuh withdraw their troops from Egypt. Amalric assumes the regency for the captive Raymond III.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=57}}{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|pp=550-551}}
'''1167'''
* ''January.'' Shirkuh invades Egypt. Amalric convokes a general assembly to Nablus which votes a 10 percent tax on movable property to finance a new campaign against Shirkuh.{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=552}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=242-243}}
* ''January 30.'' Amalric invades Egypt.{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=552}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=58}}
* ''March.'' Shawar agrees to pay a yearly tribute to Amalric and the Fatimid Caliph [[Al-Adid]] confirms their treaty.{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=552}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=243-244}}
* ''March 18.'' [[Battle of al-Babein]]: an indecisive engagement between Amalric and Shirkuh's armies.{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=244-245}}
* ''Late March.''  Shirkuh seizes Alexandria. Amalric besieges it with the assistance of a Pisan fleet.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=245}}
* ''{{circa}} August 1.'' Shirkuh agrees to abandon Alexandria in return for 40,000 dinars. Amalric is authorized to place a garrison in Alexandria. Shawar promises to pay a yearly tribute to Amalric.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=245}}
* ''August 4.'' Shirkuh and his army depart for Damascus.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=245}}
* ''Late August.'' Shawar's son, al-Kamil Shuja, offers allegiance to Nur ad-Din.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=245}} 
* ''August 29.'' Amalric marries Manuel I's niece, [[Maria Komnene, Queen of Jerusalem|Maria Komnene]], in Tyre. Amalric proposes the division of the Fatimid Caliphate between the Byzantine Empire and the Kingdom of Jerusalem to the Emperor's envoys.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=58}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=246}}
'''1168'''
* Amalric I secures the right of royal courts to judge Pisans who hold real estate in the kingdom.{{sfn|Prawer|1998|p=316}}
* ''Easter.'' The [[List of Syriac Patriarchs of Antioch from 512 to 1783|Jacobite Patriarch]] [[Michael the Syrian]] meets with Patriarch Amalric in Jerusalem.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=196}}
* ''September.'' Manuel I accepts Amalric's offer for a joint military campaign against the Fatimid Caliphate.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=246}}{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|pp=556-557}}
* ''Early October.'' The [[Grand Master of the Knights Hospitallers]], [[Gilbert of Assailly]], promises support to Amalric against Egypt. The Knights Templars decide not to participate in the campaign.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=249}}
* ''November 4.'' Amalric's troops massacre the Muslim and Coptic townspeople at Bilbeis which stirs up the Egyptians' resistance.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=58}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=168}}
* ''November 13.'' Amalric lays siege to Cairo. Al-Adid seeks Nur ad-Din's assistance, but Shawar offers a tribute to Amalric.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=58}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=251}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=169}}
* ''December 25.'' Shirkuh invades Egypt, forcing Amalric to lift the siege of Cairo.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=58}}
'''1169'''
* ''January 2.'' Amalric withdraws his troops from Egypt.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=170}}
* ''January 18.'' Shirkuh's nephew, [[Saladin]], kills Shawar with Al-Adid's approval. Al-Adid appoints Shirkuh as vizier.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=170}}
* ''March 23.'' Shirkuh dies.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=170}}
* ''March 26.'' Al-Adid appoints Saladin as vizier.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=59}}
* ''Summer.'' Amalric sends an embassy to France, England and Sicily to ask for a new crusade.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=253}}
* ''September.'' A Byzantine fleet arrives at Acre.{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=557}}
* ''October–December.'' The Franks and the Byzantines unsuccessfully besiege Damietta.{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|pp=557-558}}
'''{{circa}} 1170'''
* Amalric's only son and heir, Baldwin, is diagnosed with [[leprosy]].{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=264}}  
'''1170'''
* ''December.'' Saladin destroys the Frank colonists' unfortified quarters at [[Darum]] and Gaza.{{sfn|Prawer|1998|pp=107-109}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=257}}
'''1171'''
* ''Early.'' New embassy is sent to the European rulers.{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=257-258}}
* ''March–July.'' Amalric convinces Manuel I to renew their alliance in Constantinople.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=60}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=258}}
* ''September 13.'' Al-Adid's death put an end to the Fatimid Caliphate and makes Saladin the undisputed ruler of Egypt.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=257}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|pp=172-173}}{{sfn|Hillenbrand|1999|p=118}}
* ''October.'' Saladin invades the kingdom and destroys the Frank colonists' quarter at Montreal. He returns to Egypt when he learns of Nur ad-Din's decision to participate in the campaign. Nur ad-Din accuses Saladin of disloyalty.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=173}}{{sfn|Prawer|1998|p=111}}
'''1173'''
* Outraged by the fall of the Fatimids, the Assassin leader, [[Rashid ad-Din Sinan]], offers to convert to Christianity if the Templars do not tax the Assassins' subjects in Syria. Templars murder Sinan's envoys.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|pp=172-173}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=259}}
* ''Summer.'' Amalric sents a new embassy to Europe.{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=561}}
'''1174'''
* ''May 15.'' Nur ad-Din dies in Damascus.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=175}}
* ''June.'' Amalric besieges Banias, but falls seriously ill.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=61}}
* ''July 11.'' Amalric dies in Tiberias.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=61}}
