===Decline and fall===
{{Quote box
|quote=''"All the Christians, men and women, had assembled and were formed in two lines at the bride's door. Trumpets, flutes, and all the musical instruments were played until she emerged between two men who held her right and left... . She was most elegantly garbed in a beautiful dress from which trailed ... a long train of golden silk. On her head she wore a golden diadem covered by a net of woven gold, and on her breast was a like arrangement. Proud she was in her ornaments and dress, walking with little steps of half a span, like a dove or in the manner of a wisp of cloud. God protect us from the seduction of the sight. Before her went Christian notables in their finest and most splendid clothing, their trains falling in behind them. ... The Muslims and other Christian onlookers formed two ranks along the route, and gazed upon them without reproof."''
|source = Ibn Jubayr's report of a wedding in Tyre
|width  = 25%
|align  = right
}}
'''1174'''
* ''July 15.'' The ailing 13-year-old Baldwin IV is crowned king in the Holy Sepulchre. The senechal, [[Miles of Plancy]], rules the kingdom.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=264}}{{sfn|Philips|2010|p=115}}
* ''July 28.'' A Sicilian fleet besieges Alexandria. Conflicts between Miles and Humphrey III prevent the mobilization of the Jerusalemite army.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=263}}
* ''August 1.'' The Sicilians lift the siege of Alexandria.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=61}}
* ''August.'' Raymond III claims the regency as Baldwin IV's closest male relative.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=265}}
* ''Early October.'' Miles is assassinated in Acre. His widow, [[Stephanie of Milly]], accuses Raymond III of plotting against him.{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=592}}
* ''Late October.'' The [[High Court of Jerusalem]] elects Raymond III as baillif. He marries the Princess of Galilee, [[Eschiva of Bures]].{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=263-264}}
* ''October–December.'' Saladin occupies Damascus and Hama, forcing Nur ad-Din's son, [[As-Salih Ismail al-Malik]], to withdraw to Aleppo.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=61}}
'''1175'''
* ''January–February.'' Raymond III leads a relieve army to Hama against Saladin. He abandons the campaign after Saladin releases the hostages held for his ransom.{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=263-264}}  
* ''July 22.'' Saladin and Raymond III conclude a truce.{{sfn|Lock|2006|pp=62-63}}
'''1176'''
* ''Summer.'' The atabeg of Aleppo, Gümüshtekin, releases Raynald of Châtillon and Baldwin IV's maternal uncle, [[Joscelin III of Courtenay]].{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=267}}
* ''July.'' Baldwin IV comes of age.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=267}}
* ''July–August.'' Baldwin IV and Raymond III make raids as far as Damascus.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=63}}
* ''Late August.'' Baldwin IV appoints Joscelin III as senechal and arranges his marriage with a wealthy heiress, Agnes of Milly.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=63}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=268}}
* ''September 17.'' [[Battle of Myriokephalon]]: the Seljuk Sultan of Rum [[Kilij Arslan II]] overcomes Manuel I's army.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=63}}
* ''November.'' [[William of Montferrat, Count of Jaffa and Ascalon|William Longsword]]{{mdash}}the eldest son of [[William V, Marquess of Montferrat]]{{mdash}}marries Baldwin IV's sister, [[Sibylla, Queen of Jerusalem|Sibylla]]. William is made the count of Jaffa and Ascalon.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=266}}{{sfn|Philips|2010|p=116}}
* ''Winter.'' Raynald is sent to Constantinople to negotiate with Manuel I.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=267}}
'''1177'''
* ''Spring.'' Raynald marries the lady of Oultrejourdain, Stephanie of Milly. Baldwin IV grants Hebron to him.{{sfn|Barbar|2012|p=268}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=64}}
* ''June.'' William Longsword dies.{{sfn|Philips|2010|p=116}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=266-267}}
* ''Summer.'' Baldwin IV's health gets worse.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=64}}
* ''August 1.'' Baldwin IV's cousin, [[Philip I, Count of Flanders]] arrives at Acre. He refuses to assume the regency for Baldwin IV.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=64}}
* ''August.'' A Byzantine fleet arrives at Acre, but the Franks refuse to participate in a joint campaign against Egypt.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=64}}{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=595}}
* ''Autumn.'' Raynald is appointed as "procurator of the kingdom and the army".{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=271}}
* ''September.'' Philip I, Raymond III and Bohemond II launch a military campaign in Syria, taking the bulk of the Jerusalemite army with them.{{sfn|Philips|2010|p=269}}
* ''Late November.'' Saladin launches a sudden attack against Ascalon.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=270}}
* ''November 25.'' [[Battle of Montgisard]]: Baldwin IV routes Saladin.{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=595}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=270-271}}
'''1178'''
* ''January.'' The birth of William Longsword's posthumous son by Sybilla, [[Baldwin V of Jerusalem|Baldwin]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=64}}
* ''October.'' Baldwin IV orders the building of the fortress La Chastellet at [[Daughters of Jacob Bridge|Jacob's Ford]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=65}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=272, 274}}
'''1179'''
* ''February.'' The grand masters of the Templars and the Hospitallers, [[Odo de St Amand]] and [[Roger de Moulins]], sign an agreement to settle their disputes.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=271}}
* ''April.'' Baldwin IV gives La Chastellet to the Templars. Humphrey III dies after receiving fatal wounds during a raid against Banias. Agnes of Courtney's favorite, Aimery of Lusignan is made as constable.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=65}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=272, 274}}{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|pp=596-597}}
* ''May.'' Saladin raids the region of Jacob's Ford.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=272}}
* ''June 10.'' [[Battle of Marj Ayyun]]: Saladin routes Baldwin IV.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=273}}
* ''August 29.'' Saladin destroys La Chastellet.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=65}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=273}}
* ''September.'' Saladin makes raids as far as Beirut and Tyre.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=273}} 
'''{{circa}} 1180'''
* According to a letter of grant, the burghers of Palmeria are entitled to freely dispose of their property, but they cannot sell it to clerics or the military orders.{{sfn|Prawer|1998|p=138}}
'''1180'''
* ''April 20.'' Bohemond II and Raymond III march to Jerusalem unexpectedly. Regarding their action as an attempt to dethrone him, Baldwin IV hastily marries off Sybilla to Aimery's brother, Guy of Lusignan.{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|pp=596-597}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=274-275}}
* ''May.'' Saladin accepts Baldwin IV's proposal to a two-year-truce.{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=595}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=66}}
* ''Autumn.'' Baldwin IV's half-sister, [[Isabella I of Jerusalem|Isabella]], is betrothed to Raynald's stepson, [[Humphrey IV of Toron]]. Humphrey IV cedes his paternal domains to the king.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=275}}
* ''October 6.'' Patriarch Amalric dies.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=78}}
* ''October 16.'' [[Patriarch Heraclius of Jerusalem|Heraclius, Archbishop of Caesarea]] is elected as Latin patriarch.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=80}}
'''1181'''
* ''January 16.'' [[Pope Alexander III]] calls for a new crusade, emphasizing that the leper Baldwin IV is unable to defend the Holy Land.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=67}}{{sfn|Philips|2010|p=122}}
* ''Summer.'' Ignoring the truce, Raynald attacks a caravan.{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|pp=598-599}}
'''1182'''
* ''Spring.'' Baldwin IV prohibits Raymond III to enter the kingdom.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=277}}
* ''April.'' [[Andronikos I Komnenos|Andronikos Komnenos]]' coup in Constantinople puts an end to Frankish influence in the Byzantine Empire.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=67}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=277}}
* ''Summer.'' Baldwin IV keeps the royal army continuously in the field because of a series of raids from Syria and Egypt.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=278}}
* ''August.'' Saladin besieges Beirut, but Baldwin IV relieves it.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=278}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|pp=67-68}}
* ''September.'' Baldwin IV recaptures the fort of Habis Jaldak.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=68}}
'''1183'''
* ''February.'' A general council levies an extraordinary tax to cover the increasing defense costs. Raynald's fleet launches a raid on the [[Red Sea]], menacing [[Mecca]] and [[Medina]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=68}}{{sfn|Philips|2010|pp=119-120}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=279}}
* ''June 11.'' Saladin captures Aleppo.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=68}}
* ''September 29.'' Saladin invades Galilee.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=281}}
* ''October.'' Baldwin IV appoints Guy as baillif. The Frank troops assemble at the Springs of Saffuriya and Saladin returns to Syria. Guy's opponents accuses him of losing the opportunity to inflict a decisive defeat on Saladin.{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=281-282}}{{sfn|Philips|2010|p=121}}
* ''November.'' Guy refuses to exchange Jerusalem for Tyre with Baldwin IV. Humphrey IV marries Isabella in Kerak. Saladin [[Siege of Kerak|besieges Kerak]] during the wedding.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=283}}
* ''November 20.'' Baldwin IV orders Patriarch Heraclius to make preparations for the annulment of Guy and Sybilla's marriage. Sybilla's five-year-old son by William Longsword, Baldwin V, is crowned king.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=283}}
* ''December 3 or 4.'' Baldwin IV and Raymond III relieve Kerak.{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=284-285}}
* ''December.'' Guy and Sybilla withdraw to Ascalon. Baldwin IV deprives him of Jaffa.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=68}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=285}}
'''1184'''
* ''March 29.'' Patriarch Heraclius excommunicates [[William of Tyre]], forcing him to abdicate the chancellorship.{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=286-287}}
* ''June.'' Envoys are sent to Europe to ask for a new crusade.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=69}}
* ''Augustus 23–September 5.'' Second siege of Kerak by Saladin, but Baldwin IV relieves the fortress.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=69}}
* ''October.'' Guy pillage a Beduin tribe in a royal domain.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=285}}
* ''Late.'' [[Ibn Jubayr]], a renowned poet from [[Al-Andalus]], travels through the kingdom. He notes that the local Muslim peasants prefer the Franks' rule because they are required to pay less taxes than their peers in the Muslim countries.{{sfn|Phillips|2010|pp=42, 46}} 
'''1185'''
* ''Early April.'' The dying Baldwin IV appoints Raymond III as baillif for Baldwin V for ten years, but Joscelin III is made Baldwin V's guardian. The High Court rules that the Pope, the Holy Roman Emperor and the kings of France and England are to choose between Sybilla and Isabella's claims to the throne in case of Baldwin V's premature death.{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=289-290, 365}}{{sfn|Philips|2010|pp=121-122}}
* ''{{circa}} April 15.'' Baldwin IV dies.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=365}}
* ''Spring.'' Saladin and Raymond III sign a truce which enables Saladin to invade Mosul.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=290}}{{sfn|Philips|2010|p=123}}
* A Byzantine monk, [[John Phokas]], makes a pilgrimage in the Holy Land. He visits Orthodox monasteries which have been rebuilt during the previous decades.{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=154}}
'''1186'''
* ''March 4.'' [[Izz ad-Din Mas'ud]], the emir of Mosul, acknowledges Saladin's sovereignty.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=70}}
* ''July 20–{{circa}} September 15.'' Baldwin V dies. Raymond III leaves Jerusalem before the funeral and summons his partisans to a general assembly at Nablus. Joscelin III takes possession of Jerusalem, Acre and Beirut. Ignoring Raymond III's objections, Raynald and the grand master of the Templars, [[Gerard de Ridefort]], accompany Sybilla to the Holy Sepulchre and Patriarch Heraclius crowns her queen. Her supporters cannot persuade her to divorce Guy and she crowns him king.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=70}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=293-295}}{{sfn|Philips|2010|p=124}}
* ''October.'' Raymond III and his supporters offer the crown to Sybilla's half-sister, Isabella, and her husband, Humphrey IV in Nablus. Humphrey IV fleeds from Nablus and swears fealty to Sybilla and Guy. All his former supporters, but Raymond III and Baldwin of Ibelin, hurry to pay homage to the royal couple. Raymond III seeks Saladin's alliance against Guy.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=70}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=295-296}}
'''1187'''
* ''Early.'' Contrary to the truce, Raynald seizes a caravan and Guy cannot persuade him to return the spoils and the prisoners.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=297}}
* ''March 29.'' Saladin declares the ''jihad'' against the crusaders.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=297}}
* ''Late April'' Raymond III allows Saladin's commander [[Gökböri|Muzzafar al-Din]] to march across Galilee.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=298}} 
* ''May 1.'' [[Battle of Cresson]]: Muzzafar al-Din annihilates an army of Hospitallers and Templars.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=70}}
* ''May 2.'' Raymond III's Galilean vassals persuade him to abandon his alliance with Saladin and to make peace with Guy.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=71}}{{sfn|Philips|2010|pp=125-126}}
* ''June 26.'' After gathering more than 30,000 troops, Saladin invades the Kingdom of Jerusalem. The Frank troops start gathering at Saffuriya and the garrisons are reduced to the minimum in most fortresses and towns.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=71}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=299}}
* ''July 4.'' Saladin annihilates the army of the Kingdom of Jerusalem in the [[Battle of Hattin]]. The Frank commanders fell into captivity. Raynald, the Hospitallers and the Templars are executed.{{sfn|Hillenbrand|1999|p=345}}{{sfn|Philips|2010|pp=130-131}}
* ''July 5.'' Tiberias surrenders to Saladin.{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=615}}
* ''July 9.'' Saladin captures Acre.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=299}}{{sfn|Baldwin|1969|p=615}}
* ''July 14.'' William Longsword's brother, [[Conrad of Montferrat]], arrives at Tyre and begins to organise the resistance. He grants privileges to the Pisans in return for their assistance.{{sfn|Lock|2006|pp=70-71}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=308}}{{sfn|Prawer|1998|p=316}}
* ''July 10–September 4.'' Saladin captures Jaffa, Arsuf, Caesarea, Haifa, [[Sidon]] and Ascalon.{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=308-309}}
* ''October 2.'' After receiving a free passage to the townspeople for a huge ransom, the defenders of Jerusalem surrender to Saladin.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=72}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=311}}
