== Second kingdom ==
=== Recovery ===
'''1192'''
* ''September 2.'' A truce between Saladin and Richard I confirms the Franks' rule on the coast from Tyre to Jaffa.{{sfn|Tyerman|2006|p=461}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|pp=214-215}}
* ''October 9.'' Richard I departs for England.{{sfn|Tyerman|2006|p=472}}
* ''{{circa}} October 15.'' Saladin grants parts of [[Tel Yokneam (Qamun)|Caymont]] to [[Balian of Ibelin]] and half of Sidon to [[Reginald of Sidon]]. Henry I restores Haifa, Caesarea and Arsuf to their previous lords and grants Jaffa to Aimery of Lusignan.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=524}}
'''1193'''
* ''March 4.'' Saladin dies in Damascus. Conflicts between his sons, brothers and nephews cause the disintegration of [[Ayyubid dynasty|his empire]].{{sfn|Tyerman|2006|p=472}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|pp=216-218}}
* ''May.'' Henry I limits the Pisans' presence in Acre for their alliance with Guy. They pillage the coast and Henry I expels them from the entire kingdom. He imprisons Guy's brother, Aimery, but the barons and the grand masters persuade him to release Aimery.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|pp=524-525}}
'''{{circa}} 1194'''
* The canons of the Holy Sepulchre elect [[Aymar the Monk]] as the Latin patriarch without consulting Henry I. He imprisons them, but Archbishop Joscius mediate a reconciliation. [[Pope Celestine III]] confirms Aymar's election.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|pp=244-245}}
'''1194'''
* ''Spring.'' [[Leo I, King of Armenia|Leo II of Cilicia]] captures Bohemond III. Henry I hurries to [[Sis (ancient city)|Sis]] and achieves his release.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=79}}{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=527}}
* ''May.'' Aimery inherits Cyprus from Guy. He concludes an agreement with Henry I and mediates a reconciliation between Henry I and the Pisans.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=79}}{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=525}}
'''1195'''
* ''August 1.'' The Pope urges [[Henry VI, Holy Roman Emperor]] to launch a new crusade.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=80}}
'''1196'''
* ''Summer.'' German crusaders arrive at Acre.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=529}}
* ''July.'' Al-Adil seizes Damascus from Saladin's son, [[Al-Afdal ibn Salah ad-Din|Al-Afdal]].{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=218}}
'''1197'''
* ''Early September.'' Al-Adil captures Jaffa. The German crusaders ignore Henry I's ban and make raids against Muslim territories.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=80}}{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=529}}
* ''September 10.'' Henry I falls from the window of the royal palace and dies in Acre.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=529}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=81}}
* ''{{circa}} September 15.'' Some baron offer the throne to [[Raoul of Saint Omer]], but the military orders achieve the election of Aimery as king.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|pp=529-530}}
* ''October.'' Aimery marries Isabella. Patriarch Aymar crowns them king and queen. Aimery has his seat at Acre, but he keeps the administration of the two realms separate.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|pp=530-531}}
* ''Late October.'' German and Frank troops seize Sidon and Beirut.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=530}}
* ''November 28.'' The Germans and the Franks besiege Toron.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=530}}
'''1198'''
* ''Early.'' Aimery accuses Raoul and [[Hugh II of Saint Omer]] of an unsuccessful attempt on his life and banishes them from the kingdom. They appeal to their peers, but Aimery does not repeal his decision.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|pp=26, 29-30}} 
* ''February 2.'' The siege of Toron is abandoned after news of the death of [[Henry VI, Holy Roman Emperor]] reaches the crusaders' camp.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=530}}
* ''June 1.'' A new truce with Al-Adil.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=81}}{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|pp=530-531}}
* ''August 15.'' [[Pope Innocent III]] proclaims the [[Fourth Crusade]] in the bull ''[[Post Miserabile]]''.{{sfn|Philips|2010|p=170}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=82}}
'''1200'''
* ''February.'' Al-Adil takes control of Egypt.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=218}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=82}}
* The Pope urges the women to make donations for the crusaders instead of joining a crusade.{{sfn|Hodgson|2007|p=44}}
'''1202'''
* ''Spring.'' Reginald of Dampierre and 300 crusaders land at Acre. They leave for Antioch after Henry I prohibits them to break the truce.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=83}}{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=531}}
'''1203'''
* ''May.'' The leaders of the Fourth Crusade decide to attack Constantinople.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=84}}
'''1204'''
* ''May.'' Aimery sends a fleet to raid the Nile Delta.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=531}}{{sfn|Perry|2013|p=56}}
* ''April 12.'' The crusaders capture Constantinople. The establishment of the [[Latin Empire of Constantinople]] weakens the position of the Kingdom of Jerusalem, because the new crusader states on the ruins of the Byzantine Empire attract many crusaders from Europe.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=86}}{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=532}}
* ''September.'' Aimery and Al-Adil conclude a six-year truce. The Franks take full control of Sidon, Lydda and Ramla.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=86}}{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=532}}
'''1205'''
* ''May 1.'' Aimery dies in Acre.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=532}}
* ''Late.'' Isabella dies. Her daughter by Conrad, [[Maria of Montferrat]], succeeds her. Isabella's half-brother, [[John of Ibelin, the Old Lord of Beirut|John of Ibelin]], assumes the regency for the 13-year-old queen.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=87}}{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=532}}
'''{{circa}} 1206'''
* The barons propose Maria to the married [[Peter II of Aragon]], but the Pope does not annul Peter's marriage.{{sfn|Perry|2013|p=40}}
'''1206'''
* After being appointed as the Latin patriarch by the Pope, [[Albert of Vercelli]] comes to the Holy Land.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=250}}
'''{{circa}} 1207'''
* Patriarch Albert completes a regulation for the [[Carmelites|hermits living on Mount Carmel]] at the request of their head, [[Saint Brocard|Brocard]].{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=252}}
'''1208'''
* The barons send [[Aymar de Lairon|Aymar, Lord of Caesarea]], and Walter of Florence, [[Latin Catholic Diocese of Acre|Bishop of Acre]], to France to ask Philip II to appoint a husband for Maria. Philip II names [[John of Brienne]] as his candidate.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=536}}{{sfn|Perry|2013|p=47}}
'''1209'''
* The Pope approves John's candidacy and gives 40,000 marks for the defence of the Holy Land.{{sfn|Perry|2013|pp=47-48}}
'''1210'''
* ''July.'' Al-Adil proposes 10 villages in return for the renewal of the truce, but the Templars and the prelates prevent the High Court from accepting the offer.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=536}}{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=251}}
* ''September 13.'' John and his retinue of 300 knight land at Haifa.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=536}}
* ''September 14.'' John marries Maria in Acre.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=536}}
* ''October 3.'' John and Maria are crowned in Tyre. Al-Adil's son, [[Al-Mu'azzam Isa]], makes a raid against Acre.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=536}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=89}}{{sfn|Perry|2013|p=55}}
* ''October.'' John launches a plundering raid as far as the Jordan.{{sfn|Perry|2013|p=56}}
'''1211'''
* ''Spring.'' John sends [[Walter of Montbéliard]] to launch a naval raid against the Nile Delta.{{sfn|Perry|2013|p=56}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=90}}
* ''Summer.'' John sends 50 knights to assist the Templars against Leo in Cilicia.{{sfn|Perry|2013|p=67}}
'''1212'''
* ''July.'' John and Al-Adil conclude a six-year truce.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=90}}{{sfn|Perry|2013|pp=56-57}} 
* ''Late.'' Maria dies after giving birth to a daughter, [[Isabella II of Jerusalem|Isabella]]. After some barons challenge John's right to rule the kingdom, he sends his chancellor, [[Raoul of Merencourt]], to the Holy See. The Pope menaces those who do not obey to John with ecclesiastical sanctions.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=252}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=90}}{{sfn|Perry|2013|pp=68, 74}}
'''1213'''
* ''Early.'' [[Hugh I of Cyprus]] imprisons a group of John's supporters.{{sfn|Perry|2013|p=77}}
* ''Late April.'' The Pope proclaims the [[Fifth Crusade]] in his bull ''[[Quia maior]]''.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=90}}
'''1214'''
* John marries Leo II's daughter, [[Stephanie of Armenia]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=90}}
* A cleric murders Patriarch Albert. Raoul of Merencourt is elected as the Latin patriarch.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=252}}{{sfn|Perry|2013|p=73}}
'''1215'''
* [[Francis of Assisi]]'s disciple, Giles, settles in the kingdom.{{sfn|Perry|2013|p=76}}
'''1217'''
* ''October.'' [[Andrew II of Hungary]] and [[Leopold VI of Austria]] arrive at Acre. Troops from Antioch and Cyprus join the crusaders.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|pp=538-539}}
* ''November.'' The crusaders capture Beisan.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=90}}
* ''November 29–December 7.'' The crusaders cannot take the Muslim fortress on [[Mount Tabor]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=90}}{{sfn|Perry|2013|p=92}}
'''1218'''
* ''Early.'' Andrew II, Hugh I and Bohemond IV leave the crusaders' camp.{{sfn|Perry|2013|pp=92-93}}
* ''Spring.'' Caesarea is fortified. [[Château Pèlerin]] is built on the coast near Acre.{{sfn|Perry|2013|p=93}}
* ''May 29.'' The crusaders, along with troops from Jerusalem and Cyprus, lay siege to Damietta under John's command.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=92}}
* ''August 31.'' Al-Adil dies. [[Al-Kamil]] inherits Egypt, Al-Mu'azzam seizes Syria.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=93}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=225}}
* ''September.'' [[Pope Honorius III]]'s legate, [[Pelagio Galvani|Pelagius]], arrives at Damietta.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=93}}{{sfn|Perry|2013|p=101}}
'''1219'''
* ''May 2.'' Leo II dies after bequeathing Cilicia to his youngest daughter, [[Isabella, Queen of Armenia|Isabella]]. John lays claim to Cilicia on behalf of his wife and their son.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=93}}{{sfn|Perry|2013|p=112}}
* ''October.'' Al-Kamil offers to cede all lands to the west of the Jordan in Palestine to the crusaders if they leave Egypt. John is willing to accept the offer, but Pelagius rejects it.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=225}}
* ''November 5.'' The crusaders capture Damietta. John is appointed to rule the town.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=93}}
* ''Late November.'' Al-Mu'azzam sacks Caesarea.{{sfn|Perry|2013|p=113}}
'''1220'''
* ''February.'' The Pope confirms John's claim to Cilicia.{{sfn|Perry|2013|p=112}}
* ''Easter.'' Urged by his bailli, [[Garnier l'Aleman]], John returns to Acre.{{sfn|Perry|2013|pp=111, 114}}
* ''Summer (?).''  John's wife and their son die. The Pope acknowledges an other claimant as the lawful ruler of Cilicia.{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=235}}
* ''October.'' Al-Mu'azzam destroys the Templars' fortress at Destroit.{{sfn|Perry|2013|p=115}}
'''1221'''
* ''June.'' [[Louis I, Duke of Bavaria]] and German crusaders arrive at Damietta.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=94}}
* ''July 6.'' John returns to Damietta.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=94}}{{sfn|Perry|2013|p=117}}
* ''July–August.'' The crusaders march towards Cairo along the Nile, but the flood and Al-Kamil's troops trap them.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=94}}{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=234}}
* ''August 28.'' Pelagius and Al-Kadil agree about the evacuation of the crusaders from Egypt. Al-Kadil offers an eight-year truce.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=94}}{{sfn|Philips|2010|pp=227-228}}
* ''September 8.'' The crusaders leave Damietta.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=94}}
'''1222'''
* ''Summer.'' Parts of Acre are destroyed during an armed conflict between the Pisans and Genoese.{{sfn|Perry|2013|p=120}}
* ''October.'' John, Patriarch Raoul and the grand master of the Hospitallers, [[Guérin de Montaigu]], leave for Europe to ask for a new crusade and to find a husband for Isabella II. John appoints [[Odo of Montbéliard]] as baillif.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=39}}{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=541}}
'''1223'''
* ''March.'' The Pope, [[Frederick II, Holy Roman Empire]], John and the grand masters of the military orders agree about the marriage of Frederick II and Isabella II. The Emperor promise to allow John to continue to administer the kingdom.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=95}}{{sfn|Perry|2013|pp=123-124}}
* ''Summer.'' John stayes in northeastern France.{{sfn|Perry|2013|p=127}}
* ''August 6.'' John attends the coronation of [[Louis VIII of France]] at Reims.{{sfn|Perry|2013|p=128}}
* ''November–December.'' John visits England.{{sfn|Perry|2013|pp=131-132}} 
'''1224'''
* ''May.'' After making a pilgrimage to [[Santiago de Compostella]], John marries [[Berengaria of León]].{{sfn|Perry|2013|pp=129-130}}
* Patriarch Raoul dies.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=256}}
'''1225'''
* ''Early.'' [[Gerold of Lausanne]] is appointed as the Latin patriarch.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=257}}
* ''July 25.'' Frederick II promises the Pope to launch a crusade before September 1227.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=95}}{{sfn|Perry|2013|p=125}}
* ''August.'' Isabella II is crowned in Tyre before she leaves for Italy.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=96}}{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=542}}
* ''November 9.'' Frederick II marries Isabella II in Brindisi. The Jerusalemite barons who are present at the wedding pay homage to Frederick II. Frederick II sends Richer, [[Bishop of Melfi]], to the Kingdom of Jerusalem to receive the homage of the local barons.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=542}}{{sfn|Perry|2013|pp=135-136}}
'''1227'''
* ''August.'' Frederick II appoints [[Thomas, Count of Acerra]] as baillif.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=97}}
* ''September 8.'' Frederick II sails for the Holy Land, but illness forces him to return to Italy.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=97}}{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=237}}
* ''September 29.'' [[Pope Gregory IX]] excommunicates Frederick II for the breaking of his crusader oath.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=97}}{{sfn|Philips|2010|pp=230-231}}
* ''October.'' German, French and English crusaders land at Acre and assist the Franks to fortify the towns. The Teutonic Knights rebuild the castle of Montfort.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=542}}
'''1228'''
* ''Spring.'' Frederick II's marshal, [[Richard Filangieri]], arrives at Acre. He forbids all raids against Muslim territories.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=543}}
* ''April 25.'' The birth of [[Conrad IV of Germany|Conrad]], the only son of Frederick II by Isabella II.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=97}}
* ''May 5.'' Isabella II dies in [[Andria]] and the infant Conrad succeeds her as king of Jerusalem.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=97}}{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=238}}
* ''June 28.'' Frederick II sails for the crusade, but the Pope confirms his excommunication.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=97}}{{sfn|Philips|2010|p=232}}
* ''Late July.'' Frederick II receives the homage of the Jerusalemite barons in Limassol. He demands Beirut from John of Ibelin who refers the case to the High Court.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=97}}{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=543}}
* ''September 7.'' Frederick II lands at Acre and starts negotiations with Al-Kamil.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=98}}
'''1229'''
* ''February 18.'' Frederick II and Al-Kamil sign a truce for ten and a half year that restores Jerusalem to the Franks, but they are not allowed to fortify it. The Muslims are allowed to retain the Dome of the Rock and the [[Al-Aqsa Mosque]].{{sfn|Philips|2010|p=234}}{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|pp=544-545}}
* ''March 17.'' Frederick II enters Jerusalem.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=545}}
* ''March 18.'' Frederick II crowns himself in the Holy Sepulchre.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=545}}
* ''March 19.'' [[Peter of Limoges]], [[Archbishop of Caesarea]], places Jerusalem under an interdict because of the presence of Frederick II and the Muslims on behalf of Patriarch Gerald.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=545}}{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|pp=258-259}}

=== Absent kings ===
'''1229'''
* ''May 1.'' Frederick II departs for Italy. He appoints [[Balian Grenier]] and Garnier l'Aleman as his baillifs.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=99}}{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=546}}
* ''Summer.'' Beduins attack pilgrims on the road from Jaffa to Jerusalem and sack Jerusalem. [[Alice of Champagne]] (the daughter of Henry II and Isabella I) lays claim to Jerusalem, arguing that Conrad II forfeited the throne because he had failed to come to Jerusalem, but the High Court does not decide the case.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=99}}{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=546}}
'''1230'''
* ''May.'' Jerusalemite delegates meet with Frederick II in Foggia, but they cannot convince him to send Conrad II to the Kingdom of Jerusalem.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=100}}{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=547}}
* ''September 1.'' Pope Gregory IX lifts Frederick II's excommunication and recognizes him as the lawful ruler of Jerusalem.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=100}}{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=259}}
* ''Autumn.'' Patriarch Gerold lifts the interdict and the Catholic clerics start taking possession of the churches in Jerusalem.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=100}} 
* ''Late.'' Frederick sends Richard Filangieri to confiscate the fiefs of John of Ibelin and his allies. Filangieri besieges Beirut.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=100}}{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=548}}
'''1231'''
* ''Early.'' The High Court acknowledges Richard Filangieri as Frederick II's baillif, but maintains that no fiefs can be confiscated without a proper judgement.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=100}}{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=548}}
* ''Autumn.'' Filangieri ignores the High Court's decision and again besieges Beirut. His arbitrary act stirs up strong opposition in the towns.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=100}}{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=44}}
'''1232'''
* ''February.'' John of Ibelin march to Beirut, but he cannot relieve the fortress.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=44}}
* ''Spring.'' The townspeople form a [[Medieval commune|commune]] in Acre to guard their liberties against Filangieri. John of Ibelin comes to Acre and seizes Frederick II's fleet. He march to Tyre, forcing Filangieri to abandon the siege of Beirut.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=549}}{{sfn|Edbury|1997|pp=45-46}}
* ''May 2.'' [[Battle of Casal Imbert]]: Filangieri routes John of Ibelin near Tyre. Filangieri tries to conquer Cyprus, but Ibelin sends reinforcements from Acre, Beirut and Tyre to the island. [[Henry I of Cyprus]] who supports John of Ibelin comes of age.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=101}}{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=46}}
* ''Late May.'' John of Ibelin concludes an alliance with the Genoese and returns to Cyprus.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=47}}
* ''June 15.'' [[Battle of Agridi]]: John of Ibelin defeats Filangieri in Cyprus.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=101}}
* ''July.'' Frederick II persuades the Pope to summon Patriarch Gerold to Rome and to order the Latin Patriarch of Antioch, [[Albert of Rizzato]], to represent the Emperor's interests in the kingdom.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=48}}
* ''{{circa}} December 31.'' Frederick II appoints Philip of Maugastel as his baillif in Acre and orders the dissolution of the Commune at Acre. [[John of Caesarea]] stirs up a riot and prevents Maugastel from assuming the government. The High Court rules that Frederick II's appointments by letter are invalid and Conrad II is to come to the kingdom to appoint a new baillif. The High Court also declares Balian Grenier and Odo of Montbéliard as lawful baillifs, but Filangieri continues to administer Tyre.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=550}}{{sfn|Edbury|1997|pp=48-49}}
'''1233'''
* ''April.'' John of Ibelin expels Filangieri from Cyprus, forcing him to return to Italy to urge Frederick II to send reinforcements.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=101}}
* ''July 26.'' Patriarch Gerold sails for Rome.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=259}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=101}}
'''1234'''
* ''August.'' The Pope urges John of Ibelin to obey the Emperor.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=49}}
* ''Autumn.'' The Pope proclaims a new crusade to strengthen the defence of the Holy Land by the time the 1229 truce expires. The papal legate, Theodoric, Archbishop of Ravenna, places Acre under interdict for failing to dissolve the Commune.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=101}}{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=49}}{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=551}}
'''1235'''
* ''Early.'' The Pope cancels the ecclesiastical sanctions against Frederick II's enemies and the townspeople of Acre, fearing of their conversion to Oriental Christianity.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=49}} 
* ''October.'' Jerusalemite troops support the Hospitallers against [[Al-Muzaffar Umar]], the emir of [[Hama]].{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=550}}{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=50}}
'''1236'''
* ''Early.'' John of Ibelin dies after a riding accident.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=50}}
* ''February.'' The delegates of the burghers of Acre agree to dissolve the Commune of Acre at their meeting with the Pope, but the townspeople do not ratify the agreement.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|pp=49-50}}
* ''Spring/Summer.'' Relationship between the Pope and Frederick II becomes tense after the Emperor's campaigns in Italy.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=102}}
'''1237'''
* The Pope sends Patriarch Gerold back to the kingdom, also appointing him as papal legate.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=259}}
* The Jacobite patriarch [[Ignatius III David]] presents a statement of faith to the Dominicans during his visit in Jerusalem.{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=154}}
'''1238'''
* ''March 9.'' Al-Adil dies. His son, [[Al-Adil II]], succeeds him in Egypt, but he is unable to seize Damascus.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=103}}
'''1239'''
* ''March 20.'' The Pope excommunicates Frederick II.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=103}}
* ''September 1.'' [[Theobald I of Navarre|Theobald I, King of Navarre]] and the [[Barons' Crusade|first crusaders from France]] lands at Acre. A Muslim army sacks the undefended Jerusalem.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=103}}{{sfn|Painter|1969|pp=472-473}}
* ''November 2.'' The crusaders leave Acre for Ascalon.{{sfn|Painter|1969|p=474}}
* ''November 12.'' [[Henry II, Count of Bar]], [[Hugh IV, Duke of Burgundy]], [[Walter IV, Count of Brienne|Walter of Brienne]] and other crusader leaders leave the main army to attack an Egyptian army near Gaza.{{sfn|Painter|1969|p=475}}
* ''November 13.'' [[Battle of Gaza (1239)|Battle of Gaza]]: the Egyptians annihilate the crusaders, killing or capturing more than 1,500 foot-soldiers. The Egyptians leave the battlefield and the grand masters of the Templars and Hospitallers dissuade Theobald I from pursuing them. The main army returns to Ascalon.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=104}}{{sfn|Painter|1969|pp=476-477}}
* ''December.'' An-Nasir Daud, emir of Kerak, captures Jerusalem and destroys the Tower of David.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=104}}{{sfn|Painter|1969|pp=477-478}}
'''1240'''
* ''Summer.'' Al-Adil II's retainers depose him and make his brother, [[As-Salih Ayyub]], the ruler of Egypt. Ayyub's opponent, [[As-Salih Ismail, Emir of Damascus]], offers the region of Sidon and the castle of Belfort to the Franks in return for their assistance against Egypt. Ismail forces the garrison of Belfort to surrender and cedes it to the Franks. Ignoring the Hospitallers' and several crusaders' opposition to the treaty, Theobald I march to Jaffa where Ismail joins him. Ayyub offers Galilee to the Franks if they remain neutral and the Hospitallers persuade Theobald I to return to Acre.{{sfn|Hardwicke|1969|p=551}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=104}}{{sfn|Painter|1969|pp=478-480}}
* ''September.'' Theobald II and [[Peter I, Duke of Brittany|Peter of Dreux]] leaves for France, but Hugh IV and [[Guigues IV of Forez]] stay behind to fortify Ascalon.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=104}}{{sfn|Painter|1969|p=481}}
* ''October 8.'' Frederick II's brother-in-law, [[Richard, 1st Earl of Cornwall|Richard of Cornwall]] and English crusaders arrive at Acre.{{sfn|Painter|1969|p=483}}
* ''November.'' Richard sends envoys to Ayyub to discuss the cession of the territories promised to Theobald I. The Templars continue to oppose the truce with Egypt.{{sfn|Painter|1969|p=484}}
'''1241'''
* ''February.'' Ayub signs the treaty with the crusaders. Galilee and the hinterland of Jaffa is restured to the kingdom which reaches its greatest territorial extent after 1187.{{sfn|Painter|1969|p=484}}{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=245}}
* ''May 3.'' Richard leave for England.{{sfn|Painter|1969|p=484}}
* ''June 7.'' Four barons{{mdash}}[[Balian of Beirut]], [[Philip of Montfort, Lord of Tyre|Philip of Montfort]], [[John of Arsuf]] and [[Geoffrey of Estreing]]{{mdash}}urge Frederick II to appoint his brother-in-law, Simon of Montfort, as baillif to put an end to the internal strifes in the kingdom.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=68}}
* ''Autumn.'' Most crusaders who has remained in the kingdom leave for Europe. Filangieri tries to seize Acre with the Hospitallers' assistance, but Philip of Montfort forces him to return to Tyre. Balian of Beirut and the Templars besiege the Hospitallers' fortress in Acre.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=69}}
'''1242'''
* ''Spring.'' Conrad II comes of age and Frederick II decides to replace Filangieri with Thomas of Acerra. The new Venetian bailli, Marsilio Zorzi demands one third of Tyre from Filangieri and makes an alliance with Frederick II's opponents. Some burghers of Tyre seeks Philip of Montfort's assistance against Filangieri.<ref group="note">Many historians write that these events happened in 1242, because Conrad II reached the age of majority at fifteen, according to the laws of Jerusalem. However, evidence conclusively proves that these events actually took place in 1242 (the year when he reached the age of majority, according to Sicilian laws). Thomas of Acerra, for instance, left Acerra for the Holy Land in 1242.</ref>{{sfn|Edbury|1997|pp=70-71}}
* ''{{circa}} June 1.'' Filangieri appoints his brother, Lother, as the commander of Tyre and leaves for Europe.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=71}}
* ''June 5.'' The High Court elects Alice (Conrad II's nearest relative who lives in the kingdom) and her third husband, [[Raoul de Soissons|Ralph of Nesle]] as baillifs.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=72}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=105}}
* ''July 10.'' Frederick II's opponents capture Tyre with Venetian and Genoese support. Only Ascalon and Jerusalem remain under the control of Frederick II's supporters.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=71}}
* ''October 30.'' The Templars sack Hebron and destroy the mosque.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=105}}
'''1243'''
* ''August.'' Frederick II grants Ascalon to the Hospitallers.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=81}}
'''1244'''
* ''April.'' Thomas of Acerra formally cedes Ascalon to the Hospitallers.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=82}}
* ''August 23.'' [[Khwarazmian dynasty|Khwarizmian Turks]], who were expelled from their homeland by the Mongols, capture Jerusalem and massacre its Christian inhabitants during their march towards Egypt. Jerusalem is lost to the Franks for ever.{{sfn|Tyerman|2006|p=771}}{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=77}}
* ''October 17.'' [[Battle of La Forbie]]: Ayyub and the Khwarazmians overcome Ismail and his allies, including the Franks from Jerusalem and Antioch. More than 90% of the knights of the military orders perish in the battlefield.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=77}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=106}}{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=246}}
'''1245'''
* ''Summer.'' [[Pope Innocent IV]] proclaims the [[Seventh Crusade]] at the [[First Council of Lyon]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=106}}
* ''October.'' Ayyub occupies Damascus.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=106}}
'''1246'''
* Alice dies and her son, Henry I of Cyprus, succeeds her as regent. He appoints Balian of Beirut as baillif and grants Tyre to Philip of Montfort.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=78}}
'''{{circa}} 1247'''
* Henry I grants the County of Jaffa and the [[Lordship of Ramla]] to [[John of Ibelin (jurist)|John of Ibelin]].{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=79}}
'''1247'''
* ''June 17.'' Ayyub occupies Tiberias.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=106}}
* ''Late June.'' Mount Tabor and Belvoir surrender to Ayyub's troops.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=107}}
* ''October 15.'' The Egyptians capture Ascalon.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=79}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=107}}
* After Balian of Beirut's death, Henry I appoints John of Arsuf as baillif.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=84}}
'''1248'''
* ''September 17.'' [[Louis IX of France]] and the French crusaders arrive at Limassol. Louis IX makes preparations for the invasion of Egypt. John of Arsuf is replaced by John Foignon as baillif.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=107}}{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=84}}
'''1249'''
* ''June 5.'' Louis IX and the crusaders start the invasion of Egypt.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=107}}
* ''Autumn.'' John of Arsuf is again appointed as baillif.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=84}}
* ''November 23.'' Ayyub dies, but his retainers keep his death secret until the arrival of his son and successor, [[Al-Muazzam Turanshah]].{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=238}}{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=250}}
'''{{circa}} 1250'''
* The ''Livre des Assises de la Cour des Bourgeois''{{mdash}}a legal treatise on the laws regarding the burghers and their courts{{mdash}}is completed.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=109}}
'''1250'''
* ''February 24.'' The Egyptians impose a blockade on the crusaders' camp.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=108}}
* ''May 2.'' Turanshah's [[Mamluk]] (or slave) guards kill him and make their commander, [[Aybak]], the new ruler of Egypt.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|pp=240-241}}{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=251}}
* ''May 6.'' Louis IX agrees to leave Egypt.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=108}}
* ''May 13.'' Louis IX arrives at Acre and becomes the actual ruler of the kingdom.{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=250}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=108}}
* ''Winter.'' The suburbs are fortified in Acre.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=108}}
'''1251'''
* ''Summer.'' Caesarea is fortified.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=109}}
'''1252'''
* ''Summer.'' Jaffa is fortified.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=109}}
'''1253'''
* ''January 18.'' Henry I dies.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=87}}
* ''March 26.'' The Pope takes John of Jaffa and his family under his protection, reserving the right to apply ecclesiastic sanctions against them or their subjects for the Holy See.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|pp=85, 87}}
* ''June.'' Louis IX sends [[William Rubruck]] and Bartholomew of Cremona to [[Karakorum]] to propose an alliance to [[Möngke Khan|Möngke]], [[Mongol Empire|Great Khan of the Mongols]], against the Muslim powers.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=109}}
'''1254'''
* ''March 6.'' Conrad II dies in [[Lavello]] in Italy. His successor, the two-year-old [[Conradin]] remains in Bavaria under the guardianship of his uncle, [[Louis II, Duke of Bavaria]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=110}}
* ''April 24.'' Louis IX leaves Acre for France. He appoints [[Geoffrey of Sergines]] as the commander of 100 knights who are left behind in the kingdom.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=110}}{{sfn|Tyerman|2006|p=722}}
'''1255'''
* ''February.'' John of Jaffa succeeds John of Arsuf as baillif. He concludes a 10-year truce with [[An-Nasir Yusuf]], the Ayyebite ruler of Damascus.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|pp=88, 90}}
* ''Late December.'' Geoffrey of Sergines makes a raid in the region of Ascalon and Gaza.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|pp=90-91}}
'''1256'''
* ''June.'' A dispute over property rights in the estates of the Baselite monastery of [[Mar Saba|Saint Sabas]] in Acre develops into an armed conflict between Genoese and Venetian merchants.The Genoese and the Pisans destroy parts of the Venetian quarter and Philip of Montfort expels the Venetians from Tyre.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=91}}
'''1257'''
* ''March.'' The emir of Jerusalem raids the region of Jaffa, but the Franks routes him.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=91}}
* ''July.'' The Venetians conclude an alliance with the Pisans.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=91}}
* ''August.'' John of Arsuf grants commercial privileges to merchants from [[Ancona]] who support the Genoese.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=91}}
* ''Autumn.'' The united Venetian and Pisan fleets defeat the Genoese at Acre.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=92}}
'''1258'''
* ''February.'' John of Arsuf and the Templars' grand master, [[Thomas Bérard]], convoke the barons and the burghers' representatives to a general assembly. They elect the infant [[Hugh II of Cyprus|Hugh II, King of Cyprus]] as regent for the absent Conrad II and appoint Hugh II's mother, [[Plaisance of Antioch]], as regent for him. The Genoese, the Hospitallers and their allies do not accept the decision. Plaisance appoints John of Arsuf as her baillif before she retuns to Cyprus.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|pp=92-93}}
* ''February.'' Möngke's brother, [[Hülegü]], occupies Bagdad. The Abbasid Caliph, [[Al-Musta'sim]] is murdered.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|pp=242-243}}{{sfn|Philips|2010|p=262}}
* ''June.'' A Venetian fleet routes the Genoese at Acre. Philip of Montfort comes to Acre to assist the Genoese, but after their defeat he returns to Tyre.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=93}}
* ''Late.'' John of Arsuf dies.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=94}}
'''1259'''
* ''May.'' Plaisance makes Geoffrey of Sergines her baillif.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=94}}
* ''September.'' The Mongols invade Syria. [[Hethum I, King of Armenia]] and [[Bohemond VI of Antioch]] join the Mongols, but the Jerusalemite barons remain neutral.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=111}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=243}}
'''1260'''
* ''January.'' The Mongols capture Aleppo.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=243}}{{sfn|Philips|2010|p=263}}
* ''March 1.'' The Mongols capture Damascus. Hülegü departs for Karakorum to participate in the election of the new great khan, accompanied by the bulk of his army.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=111}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|pp=243, 245}}
* ''Summer.'' The Mamluk Sultan of Egypt, [[Qutuz]], proposes an alliance to the Franks. The Jerusalemite barons do not accept his offer, but allow the Mamluk troops to march across the kingdom.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=245}}
* ''September 3.'' [[Battle of Ain Jalut]]: the Mameluks annihilate the Mongol army.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=246}}
* ''September 8.'' The Mamluks capture Damascus.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=246}}
* ''October 24.'' [[Baibars]] murders Qutuz and the Mamluks acclaim him sultan.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=247}}{{sfn|Philips|2010|p=265}}
'''1261'''
* John of Arsuf begins selling his estates to the Hospitallers.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=95}}
* ''September.'' Plaisance dies. Hugh II is still a minor, but his kins do not claim the regency in Jerusalem.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|pp=96, 88}}
'''1263'''
* ''March.'' Baibars pillages Nazareth and Bethlehem and destroys the Church of Nativity.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=113}}{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=258}}
* ''April 4.'' Baibars unsuccessfully besieges Acre, but he destroys the suburbs. Geoffrey of Sergines is wounded during the siege.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=113}}{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=258}}{{sfn|Edbury|1994|p=89}}
* ''April.'' Hugh II's aunt, [[Isabella of Cyprus]], comes to Acre to exercise the regency on his behalf in Jerusalem. She appoints her husband, [[Henry of Antioch]], as her deputy, but the High Court refuses to instal them without Hugh II's presence.{{sfn|Edbury|1994|p=88}}
'''1264'''
* ''June.'' The Hospitallers and the Templars make a raid into the region of Ascalon. Baibars pillages the environs of Caesarea and Chastel Pelerin.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=113}}
* ''July.'' The Pope urges the prelates, the grand masters of the military orders and the most influential barons to resolve their conflicts.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=98}}
* Isabella dies. Her son, [[Hugh III of Cyprus|Hugh of Antioch-Lusignan]], and his cousin, [[Hugh, Count of Brienne|Hugh of Brienne]], claims the right to exercise the regency on Hugh II's behalf in Jerusalem. The High Court confirms Hugh of Antioch-Lusignan's claim.{{sfn|Edbury|1994|pp=88-89}}
'''{{circa}} 1265'''
* John of Jaffa completes ''[[Le Livre des Assises]]'' (the most complete treatise on the laws of Jerusalem).{{sfn|Edbury|1997|pp=98, 105}}{{sfn|Tyerman|2006|p=729}}
'''1265'''
* ''March 5.'' Baibars captures and destroys Caesarea.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=113}}{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=258}}
* ''March 16.'' Baibars cannot take Chastel Pelerin, but he destroys Haifa.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=114}}
* ''April 30.'' Arsuf surrenders to Baibars who destroys it.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=114}}
* ''May.'' Hugh of Antioch-Lusignan comes to the kingdom accompanied by 130 knights and mounted squires.{{sfn|Edbury|1997|p=89}}
* ''October.'' [[Odo, Count of Nevers]], and 50 French crusaders arrive at Acre.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=114}}
'''1266'''
* ''January.'' [[Erhard of Valery]] and [[Erhard of Nanteuil]] lead French crusaders to Acre.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=114}}
* ''July 22.'' Baibars captures Safed, Toron and Chastel Neuf and takes control of whole Galilee.{{sfn|Edbury|1994|p=89}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=114}}
* ''October.'' Hugh of Antioch-Lusignan, Geoffrey of Sergines and the military orders make a joint raid in Galilee.{{sfn|Edbury|1994|p=89}}
'''1267'''
* ''March 27.'' Louis IX again takes the Cross in France.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=114}}
* ''December.'' Hugh II dies and Hugh of Antioch-Lusignan succeeds him.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=114}}{{sfn|Edbury|1994|p=90}}
'''1268'''
* ''March 7.'' Baibars captures and destroys Jaffa.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=115}}
* ''April 15.'' Belfort surrenders to Baibars.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=115}}
* ''May.'' The High Court elects Hugh III as regent for Conradin, ignoring the claim of his aunt, [[Maria of Antioch (pretender)|Maria of Antioch]].{{sfn|Edbury|1994|p=90}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=115}}
* ''August 23.'' [[Battle of Tagliacozzo]]: [[Charles I of Anjou]], [[King of Sicily]], routes Conradin in Italy.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=115}}
* ''October 29.'' Conradin is beheaded in Naples.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=115}}

=== Final years ===
'''1269'''
* ''September 24.'' Hugh III of Cyprus (great-grandson of Isabella I and Henry of Champagne) and Maria of Antioch (granddaughter of Isabella I and Aimery of Lusignan) lay claim to Jerusalem. The High Court rejects her claim and elect Hugh as king. Hugh is crowned in Tyre.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=116}}{{sfn|Erdbury|1994|p=90}}
* ''Late October.'' Two natural sons of [[James I of Aragon]], [[Fernán Sánchez]] and [[Pedro Fernández de Híjar|Pedro Fernández]], and Aragonese crusaders arrive at Acre.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=116}}
* ''November.'' Baibars routes the Aragonese crusaders near Acre.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=116}}
'''1270'''
* ''July 20.'' Louis IX and the French crusaders land at Tunis, because he thinks that [[Muhammad I al-Mustansir]], the emir of Tunis is willing to convert to Christianity.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=116}}{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=253}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=251}}
* ''August 25.'' Louis IX dies near Tunis.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=116}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=251}}
* ''November 11.'' The French crusaders depart from Tunis for France.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=116}}
* The Venetians and the Genoese conclude a truce. The Genoese are allowed to return to Acre.{{sfn|Erdbury|1994|p=94}}
'''1271'''
* ''May 9.'' The crown prince of England, [[Edward I of England|Edward]], and English crusaders arrive at Acre.{{sfn|Tyerman|2006|p=813}}
* ''May–June.'' Edward unsuccessfully besieges Qaqun on Mount Carmel.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=117}}
* ''June 23.'' Baibars captures the Teutonic Knights' fortress at Montfort.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=117}}
* ''July.'' The Cypriot nobles denies to come to fight in the Kingdom of Jerusalem. Their leaders is John of Jaffa's son, [[James of Ibelin]].{{sfn|Erdbury|1994|p=92}}
* [[John of Montfort, Lord of Tyre]] concludes a truce with Baibars.{{sfn|Erdbury|1994|p=91}}
'''1272'''
* ''May 12.'' Hugh and Baibars conclude a 10-year truce.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=117}}{{sfn|Erdbury|1994|p=92}}
* ''{{circa}} September 30.'' Edward and the English crusaders depart for England.{{sfn|Tyerman|2006|p=813}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=117}}
'''1274'''
* ''May 7–July 17.'' [[Second Council of Lyon]]: a plan for a new crusade is adopted. [[Pope Gregory X]] persuades Charles I of Anjou to start negotiations about the purchase of Mary of Antioch's claim to Jerusalem.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=118}}
'''1275'''
* ''March.'' After the death of [[Bohemond VI of Antioch]] (who ruled the remnants of the Principality of Antioch and the County of Tripoli), Hugh claims the regency for the 14-year-old [[Bohemond VII of Antioch|Bohemond VII]], but the High Court of Antioch elects Bohemond VII's mother, [[Sibylla of Armenia]], to the post.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=118}}
'''1276'''
* ''October.'' After a debate about the purchase of an estate near Acre by the Templars without his consent, Hugh leaves for Cyprus.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=118}}{{sfn|Erdbury|1994|p=95}}
'''1277'''
* ''March 18.'' Maria of Antioch sells her claim to Jerusalem to Charles I with the Pope's consent. The Venetians, the Templars and the French garrison in Acre support Charles I.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=119}}{{sfn|Erdbury|1994|pp=93-95}}
* ''May–June.'' Charles I appoints [[Roger of San Severino]] as his baillif. San Severino takes possession of the royal castle in Acre without opposition.{{sfn|Erdbury|1994|p=95}}
* ''July 1.'' Baibars dies and his son, [[Al-Said Barakah]], succeeds him.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=119}}
* ''July.'' [[Guillaume de Beaujeu]], the Templars' grand master, mediates a reconciliation between John of Montfort and the Venetians. The Venetians acknowledge John's rule in Tyre and John restore their quarter to them.{{sfn|Erdbury|1994|p=95}}
* ''September.'' Patriarch Thomas dies. The canons of the Holy Sepulchre ask the Pope to translate the [[Archbishop of Naples]] (whose see was located in Charles I's realm) to Jerusalem.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=277}}
'''1279'''
* ''May.'' [[Pope Honorius IV]] appoints Elias, [[Bishop of Périgueux]], as the Latin Patriarch.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=277}}
* ''August.'' [[Al-Mansur Qalawun]] becomes the sultan of Egypt.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=119}}
* Hugh leads an army to Tyre to fight against San Severino, but the Templars prevents him to attack Acre.{{sfn|Erdbury|1994|p=95}}
'''1281'''
* ''May.'' Qalawun concludes a truce with the Kingdom of Jerusalem.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=119}}
'''1282'''
* ''April.'' After the [[Sicilian Vespers]], Charles I recalls San Severino to Italy. Before leaving Acre, San Severino appoints [[Odo Poilechien]] as his deputy in Acre.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=120}}{{sfn|Erdbury|1994|p=96}}
'''1283'''
* [[Burchard of Mount Sion]] completes his ''Description of the Holy Land'' about his travels in the Holy Land and the neighboring territories.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=120}}
'''1284'''
* ''March 4.'' Hugh dies in Tyre. His 17-year-old son, [[John II of Jerusalem|John II]], is recognized as his successor in Jerusalem only in Beirut and Tyre.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=120}}
'''1285'''
* ''January 7.'' Charles I dies. His son and successor, [[Charles II of Naples]], also inherits his claim to Jerusalem.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=121}}
* ''May 20.'' John II dies. His brother, [[Henry II of Jerusalem|Henry II]], succeeds him.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=121}}
'''1286'''
* ''June 24.'' Henry II arrives at Acre. The military orders acknowledge him as the lawful king of Jerusalem.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=121}}
* ''June 29.'' Odo Poilechien surrenders to the citadel of Acre to Henry II.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=121}}
* ''August 15.'' Henry II is crowned in Tyre.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=121}}
'''1287'''
* ''May.'' Qalawun occupies the last remnants of the County of Tripoli.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=122}}
* ''{{circa}} December 31.'' Patriarch Elias dies in Rome.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=278}}
'''1289'''
* ''Early.'' [[Pope Nicholas IV]] appoints [[Nicholas of Hanapes]] as Latin Patriarch.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=278}}
* ''July.'' Qalawun and Henry II conclude a 10-year truce.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=256}}
'''1290'''
* ''Early.'' Pope Nicholas IV calls for a new crusade for the defence of Acre.{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=260}}
* ''{{circa}} August 15.'' Italian crusaders arrive at Acre and murder Muslim merchants.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=256}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=122}}
* ''Late August.'' Drunken Italian crusaders massacre all bearded men in Acre. Qalawun demands the [[extradition]] of the murderers, but the Frank authorities refuse it.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|pp=256-257}}
* ''November 10.'' Qalawun dies. His son, [[Al-Ashraf Khalil]], succeeds him.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=122}} 
'''1291'''
* ''April 5.'' Al-Ashraf Khalil lays [[Siege of Acre (1291)|siege to Acre]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=122}}
* ''Early May.'' Henry II and Cypriot knights come to Acre.{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=260}}
* ''May 19.'' Tyre surrenders without resistance.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=122}}
* ''Late May.'' After the Mamluks occupies the Templars' keep, Henry II fleeds from Acre. Patriarch Nicholas drowns while fleeing from the town.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=278}}{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=260}}
* ''May 28.'' The Mamluks capture Acre. The burghers are massacred or enslaved.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=122}}{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=260}}
* ''July 14.'' The Mamluks capture Sidon.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=122}}
* ''July 31.'' Beirut surrenders to the Mameluk troops.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=122}}

== Aftermath ==
'''1290s'''
* Henry II issues new Cypriot coins with an inscription referring to his title of king of Jerusalem, and displaying the [[Cross of Jerusalem]] on the reverse.{{sfn|Edbury|1994|p=109}} 
'''1291'''
* ''August.'' [[Pope Nicholas IV]] calls for a new crusade for the recovery of the Holy Land.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=122}}
'''1295'''
* Charles II offers his claim to Jerusalem to [[James II of Aragon]] during their negotiations about Sicily.{{sfn|Edbury|1994|p=107}}
'''1299'''
* Charles II offers his claim to Jerusalem to [[Frederick III of Sicily]] as part of his daughter's dowry.{{sfn|Edbury|1994|p=107}}
'''1309–1311'''
* The Aragonese attempts to convince Charles II's successor, [[Robert, King of Naples]], to renounce his claim to Jerusalem in favor of Frederick III.{{sfn|Edbury|1994|p=107}}
'''1335'''
* During his visit in Cyprus, James of Verona is informed that the women wear black in mourning for the occupation of the towns on the Syrian coast by the Muslims.{{sfn|Edbury|1994|p=109}}
'''1365'''
* A member of the royal family is rewarded with the title prince of Galilee in Cyprus.{{sfn|Edbury|1994|p=108}}

